export const SENTENCES: PinatuboSentence[] = [{"page": 2, "text": "Copyright © 2011 by Holy Angel University All rights reserved."}, {"page": 2, "text": "No part of this book may be reproduced without the permission of the publisher."}, {"page": 2, "text": "Henson and Nick Sagmit Back cover photo from http://cache.boston.com Printed by Data Access Enterprises, Inc."}, {"page": 5, "text": "PROLOGUE I wrote this book so that all Pinatubo victims, especially my fellow Kapampangans, will be able to revisit those earth-shaking and life-changing events any time they want, without having to make a pilgrimage to the crater lake like what others do."}, {"page": 5, "text": "I have tried to reconstruct the events before, during and after the 1991 eruption but the Pinatubo story is so epic, and the personal stories of survivors so many and varied, that the best that this book can do is serve as template where readers can situate their individual experiences in the book’s timeline."}, {"page": 5, "text": "I dedicate this to those who went through the horror, the panic, the grief, and the desperation of those calamitous years, those who endured them, survived them, and ultimately triumphed over them."}, {"page": 5, "text": "I dedicate it especially to those who had the bravery and the heroism to help others despite being victims themselves."}, {"page": 5, "text": "This book is also for those who weren’t there when it happened— those who were not born yet, and those who were in another place (out of necessity and circumstance)."}, {"page": 5, "text": "I hope that through this book, they will vicariously go through the same ordeal and get the same lessons the survivors got."}, {"page": 5, "text": "I would like to acknowledge the sources of the research and photographic material in this book, beginning with Fire and Mud, co-edited by Dr."}, {"page": 5, "text": "Raymundo Punongbayan of PHIVOLCS; The Ash Warriors by Col."}, {"page": 5, "text": "Richard Anderegg; Pinatubo and the Politics of Lahar by Dr."}, {"page": 5, "text": "Pinatubo: 500 Years After by Barbara Mae Dacanay, Pinatubo: The Eruption of the Century by Eddee RH."}, {"page": 5, "text": "Castro; Pinatubo: The Triumph of the Kapampangan Spirit by Bong Lacson; the writings and collections of Paul Kekai Manansala, Dr."}, {"page": 5, "text": "It was still an analog world in the years 1991-1995; the gadgets and conveniences that we take for granted today would have made surviving and documenting Pinatubo a lot easier: bottled water, cell phones, digital cameras."}, {"page": 5, "text": "So I really appreciate those who shared their photographs: Guy ‘Indra’ Hilbero, Josie Henson, Cecile Yumul, Nick Sagmit, Edwin Tuyay, Bessie Makabali and Rod Custodio."}, {"page": 5, "text": "My gratitude to all our interviewees who shared their Pinatubo stories."}, {"page": 5, "text": "Special thanks to Elvie David, Michael Celis, Romulo Gabriana, Jr., Cecilia Pingul and Nina Tomen who also shared anecdotes and"}, {"page": 6, "text": "I would like to thank the HAU-NSTP students of School Year 2010-2011, their instructors and their administrator, Norielyn Pineda, for conducting interviews in resettlement areas."}, {"page": 6, "text": "My staffers at the Center for Kapampangan Studies were with me from beginning to end: Erlinda Cruz, Joel Mallari, Myra Paz Lopez, Ian Christopher Alfonso, and of course, Leonardo Calma, who spent long hours with me in designing this book."}, {"page": 6, "text": "Special thanks to our Center consultants: Alex Castro, Dr."}, {"page": 6, "text": "It was Francis who spearheaded the commemoration of the eruption’s 20th anniversary along with Mr."}, {"page": 6, "text": "Levy Laus and the members of the Pinatubo Memorial Day 2011 Executive Committee."}, {"page": 6, "text": "Laus gave me access to his personal Pinatubo collections which reveal the extent and importance of his role in the Save San Fernando Movement."}, {"page": 6, "text": "Thanks also to our student assistants and practicum students who transcribed the interviews: Kimberly Jill Bautista, Precious Jewel Nierva, Unice Lapuz, Lloyd Iryll Supan, Dayron Pamintuan, Knowell David, Andro Dimacali , Jon Louie Bartolo and Karen Claire Rosales."}, {"page": 6, "text": "I would like to thank the Administration of Holy Angel University, led by our President, Dr."}, {"page": 6, "text": "Villanueva, for supporting this project all the way."}, {"page": 6, "text": "Lastly I would like to give my affection and gratitude to my loved ones—my son Marvin (who was born two months after the eruption), my parents and my siblings."}, {"page": 6, "text": "The night of the eruption, we all wanted to flee but for some reason, my father refused."}, {"page": 6, "text": "It turned out to be the right thing to do."}, {"page": 6, "text": "While we endured the quakes and the ash fall that night, my mother led the rosary and that, too, turned out to be a good decision."}, {"page": 9, "text": "SEASON OF SORROWS Mount Pinatubo is the point of convergence among Pampanga, Zambales and Tarlac, the three provinces that shared the brunt of the 1991 eruption."}, {"page": 9, "text": "But it was Pampanga which took a beating."}, {"page": 9, "text": "To find anything in world history that is comparable to the season of horrific calamities that befell Kapampangans in 1991-1995, one has to get past Japan’s tsunami, Haiti’s earthquake, or the destruction of Pompeii, and go all the way back to the Old Testament, when the ten plagues ravaged Egypt."}, {"page": 9, "text": "This is not to belittle other people’s sufferings, but Kapampangans got in one serving what others got piecemeal: earthquakes, volcanic eruption, typhoons, floods, ash, rocks and sand raining down from the sky, days of darkness, swarms of locusts."}, {"page": 9, "text": "On June 15, Kapampangans found themselves within 20 kilometers of the world’s second largest volcanic eruption in 100 years."}, {"page": 9, "text": "The 1 yrutneC eht fo noitpurE ehT :obutaniP"}, {"page": 10, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard 2 )nuS ehT( euD ojoJ Left, swarms of locusts thriving in desert-like conditions of lahar deposits decimated farmlands as thousands of Kapampangans lost their homes permanently. ground shook all night—hard jolts every three minutes—which reduced even men to tears."}, {"page": 10, "text": "And in one incredible coincidence that never happened before or since, a typhoon crossed the vicinity of the volcano at the precise hour of the eruption. “This place is cursed,” Sgt."}, {"page": 10, "text": "Richard Johnson told The New York Times in 1991."}, {"page": 10, "text": "The U.S. serviceman had been assigned to Clark Air Base only two years but had already experienced violent rallies, coup attempts and NPA attacks in addition to a magnitude 7.8 earthquake in 1990 and the eruption in 1991. “Next thing we’ll probably get is a tidal wave.”1 The eruption left the United States government no option but to close down its largest offshore military base, rendering moot the ongoing negotiations for its lease extension."}, {"page": 10, "text": "It was a one-two punch that forced the region’s most progressive city, Angeles, to its knees."}, {"page": 10, "text": "Kapampangans are no strangers to natural and manmade calamities—colonization, revolutions, world war, floods, famine— but nothing prepared them for the scourge of lahars that followed the eruption."}, {"page": 10, "text": "In terms of magnitude, frequency and damage to densely populated communities, the lahars of Pampanga were unprecedented in history.2 Rivers of boiling mud, which had the sound of a thousand carabaos on a stampede, buried entire towns, one barrio at a time, sometimes repeatedly over the next five years."}, {"page": 10, "text": "It pushed Kapampangans to the limits of their faith and sanity, and made them turn against each other over where the dikes should pass and which communities should be sacrificed as catch basins."}, {"page": 11, "text": "Season of Sorrows In Mabalacat, hundreds of residents who had lost their houses in the eruption also lost their jobs when Clark closed."}, {"page": 11, "text": "They spent their hefty separation pay on new houses, which they lost again when the lahars came."}, {"page": 11, "text": "Fire and flood destroy only your home; lahars destroy even your home address, because they force your entire neighborhood to relocate, and they erase all landmarks and inundate the place repeatedly to make sure you cannot rebuild. “What else can In Bacolor, the dead in the cemetery happen other than the island sinking?” were reburied over and over, one layer at a time every monsoon season, until six feet Sgt."}, {"page": 11, "text": "Joe Nyzio US serviceman under became twenty-six feet under."}, {"page": 11, "text": "Lahars at Clark Field4 also turned two-story houses into one-story houses, and one-story houses into nothing but roofs sitting on the sand.3 Residents tried to outsmart the river by raising their houses on stilts; the next lahars, however, still reached them."}, {"page": 11, "text": "In 1995, the last of the lahar flows dealt Bacolor one final blow, killing at least 500 residents in one sweep."}, {"page": 11, "text": "It was heart-rending to watch news footage showing these supposedly proud scions of genteel families and descendants of warriors and poets crawling in mud and being herded to evacuation centers, where they lined up for their daily ration of noodles and sardines and for their turn at common toilets."}, {"page": 11, "text": "The reputation, and self-image, of Kapampangans had always been that of a vain and carefree people—the result of centuries of pampering by their colonial masters, who rewarded them with access to exclusive schools and the royal army."}, {"page": 11, "text": "In return, Kapampangans gave the colonizers—first the Spaniards, then the Americans—their dog-like loyalty, sometimes 3 )retfA sraeY 005 obutaniP .tM( zereP ynnaD"}, {"page": 12, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard tragically at the expense of their compatriots."}, {"page": 12, "text": "Still, no matter how big the karmic debt they incurred in history, Kapampangans did not deserve this punishment."}, {"page": 12, "text": "It is to their credit that as soon as the season of calamities ended, they got themselves out of the rock bottom where Pinatubo Many Kapampangans were reduced to begging on had kept them for five long the roadside, using tabo (tin or plastic cans) years."}, {"page": 12, "text": "The speed with which they made the recovery surprised the country and probably even themselves."}, {"page": 12, "text": "Kapampangans may be vain, spendthrift, lovers of the good life, even dugong aso."}, {"page": 12, "text": "But they are also the most religious people in this country."}, {"page": 12, "text": "When lahars threatened to breach a dike, Kapampangans, like the Hebrews carrying the Ark of the Covenant, picked up their religious images and took them to the edge of the river, literally to stop the waves."}, {"page": 12, "text": "Today, Kapampangans aged 20 and below have no memory of the Pinatubo eruption."}, {"page": 12, "text": "When they look at Mount Pinatubo they see a crater lake that’s valued only as a magnet for tourists, not as a remembrance of past sorrows."}, {"page": 12, "text": "It’s time to retell the amazing story of Pinatubo and the equally amazing stories of Kapampangans who endured that season of horrific calamities. 1 The New York Times, June 13, 1991. 2 Christopher G."}, {"page": 14, "text": "AncestrAl PinAtubo suMMit (original peak) Mt. negron (part of old crater rim) 1,000,000 - 500 years ago Gentle Giant Ancestral Pinatubo, born 1 million years ago, was a gentle giant compared to its petulant child, Modern Pinatubo, born 35,000 years ago."}, {"page": 14, "text": "Its continuous eruptions gradually elevated central Luzon, from Lingayen Gulf to Manila Bay."}, {"page": 17, "text": "THE GROWING MOUNTAIN 1,000,000 - 2300 years ago Long periods of sleep interrupted by fitful waking moments Before this Mount Pinatubo, there was an ancestral volcano that once stood in its place."}, {"page": 17, "text": "It was twice as high as the pre-1991 Pinatubo, and its crater twice as wide as the present caldera."}, {"page": 17, "text": "Mount Negron, Mount Dorst, Mount Donald, Mount Tayawan, Mount Cuadrado and other peaks in the Zambales Mountain Range were mere vents in the ancient volcano’s rim.1 Ancestral Pinatubo started erupting one million years ago."}, {"page": 17, "text": "From all indications, they were not huge eruptions, but they ejected enough material to elevate large areas of the midsection of Luzon island."}, {"page": 17, "text": "Scientists have unearthed Pinatubo sediments as far as Lingayen Gulf in the north and Manila Bay in the south."}, {"page": 17, "text": "Practically all of Pampanga, Zambales and Tarlac, and parts of Bulacan, Nueva Ecija, Bataan and 9 duM dna eriF"}, {"page": 18, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Pangasinan, are standing on old Pinatubo sediments.2 Mount Arayat, the conical volcano across the plain that many people often mistake for Mount Pinatubo, had its last eruptions about 600,000 years ago— which means they overlapped with those of ancestral Pinatubo."}, {"page": 18, "text": "It was probably the only time the two volcanoes erupted simultaneously."}, {"page": 18, "text": "The other volcanoes in the vicinity of ancestral Pinatubo vented magma also during this period: Mount Negron, about 5 kilometers southeast of Pinatubo; Mount Cuadrado, 11 kilometers south of Pinatubo; the Mataba dome, 11 kilometers northeast of Pinatubo; the Bituin plug, 8.5 kilometers north-northeast of Pinatubo; and the Tapungho plug, 14 kilometers southwest of Pinatubo.3 Ancestral Pinatubo quieted down about 45,000 years B.P. (Before Present), or 43,000 years before the birth of Christ."}, {"page": 18, "text": "Ten thousand years later, in 35,000 B.P., the volcano was reborn as Modern Pinatubo with an explosion or a series of explosions that can only be described as the mother of all Pinatubo eruptions. (Scientists call it the Inararo Eruptive Period, named after a village where they found deposits that yielded the data.) It was 10 times larger than the 1991 eruption, and it blanketed its surroundings with a 325-feet layer of volcanic debris.4 It’s hard to see these deposits today because 10 duM dna eriF Pre-1991 summit of Pinatubo."}, {"page": 18, "text": "The ridge in the foreground marks the rim of a prehistoric crater, from which the post-Buag summit grew."}, {"page": 19, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions they have been overtopped by ash fall and pyroclastic flows from subsequent eruptions."}, {"page": 19, "text": "Myers of the 26th Cavalry at Fort Stotsenburg saw and described them as “marvelous rock formation, reminders of the Pre-Glacial Age.”5 (He was wrong, of course: the glacier-like rocks that he thought were formed by ice were, in fact, ash and sand produced by fire and sculpted by water.) In May, 1991, volcanologists investigating the restive Pinatubo also saw these deposits along the Abacan and Sacobia river channels."}, {"page": 19, "text": "The rivers radiating from Pinatubo conveyed the prehistoric lahars to the plains of Central Luzon."}, {"page": 19, "text": "By studying the deposited material in these river valleys and channels, scientists have discovered the dates of Pinatubo’s previous eruptions."}, {"page": 19, "text": "For example, they identified the elongated outcropping on the Bamban side of Sacobia River as a pyroclastic-flow deposit from an eruption in 17,000 B.P. (called the Sacobia Eruptive Period)."}, {"page": 19, "text": "The towns of Lubao and Floridablanca stand on lahar deposits from an eruption in 9000 B.P. (called the Pasbul Eruptive Period), while much of Tarlac, including the present Hacienda Luisita, is on top of volcanic material produced by eruptions from 6000 to 5000 B.P. (the Crow Valley Eruptive Period)."}, {"page": 19, "text": "The entire area occupied by Clark Air Base was created by a series of eruptions from 3900 to 2300 B.P. (the Maraunot Eruptive Period)."}, {"page": 19, "text": "Lastly, the eruption about 500 B.P. (the Buag Eruptive Period) formed the steep summit the 1991 eruption blew off.6 Pinatubo’s eruptive history is composed of long stretches of repose alternating with spurts “Towering glaciers” are actually thick deposits of volcanic debris of volcanic activity, with the size of eruptions 11"}, {"page": 20, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Two rows of pyroclastic-flow deposits from Pinatubo’s ancient and recent eruptions: the upper cliffs reveal prehistoric debris, while the lower deposits are from the 1991 eruption. progressively diminishing and the periods of repose progressively shortening."}, {"page": 20, "text": "There was a gap of 10,000 years between the last eruption of ancestral Pinatubo and the Inararo Eruptive Period; 18,000 years between Inararo Eruptive Period and Sacobia Eruptive Period; 8,000 years between Sacobia and Pasbul; 4,000 years between Pasbul and Crow Valley; 2,700 years between Crow Valley and Maraunot; 1,600 years between Maraunot and Buag; and 500 years between Buag and the 1991 eruption."}, {"page": 20, "text": "The 1991 eruption was one of the smallest eruptions and the 500-year interval between the last two eruptions one of the shortest."}, {"page": 20, "text": "But Kapampangans need not worry: decades are but seconds and centuries mere minutes in geologic time."}, {"page": 20, "text": "To illustrate: the entire history of the Philippines—the arrival of the Spaniards, the Revolution, the American colonization, World War II, martial law, People Power—would fit in that small gap between the last two eruptions in the Pinatubo timeline. 1 Fire and Mud, p. 167. 2 Ibid., pp. 175-189. 3 Ibid., 167. 4 Ibid., 175-176. 5 H.A."}, {"page": 20, "text": "Myers, Memorandum re: Points of Interest, Fort Stotsenburg, Pampanga, P.I. (January 17, 1925). 6 Fire and Mud, pp. 175-188. 12"}, {"page": 21, "text": "THE ERUPTION bEFORE 1991 800 – 500 years ago It pushed Pampanga’s shoreline 15 kilometers from Guagua to its present location The Buag Eruptive Period, the last known volcanic activity of Pinatubo before it erupted in 1991, occurred about 500 to 800 years ago, according to French geographer Dr."}, {"page": 21, "text": "Jean Christophe- Gaillard of the Université Joseph Fourier-Grenoble I in France.1 That would put the pre-1991 eruption between late 12th century and late 15th century (1190s-1490s)."}, {"page": 21, "text": "Gaillard, a Kapampangan-speaking Frenchman who used to work for the Center for Kapampangan Studies, recently teamed up with other scientists to make an in-depth study of the pre-1991 eruption using the multidisciplinary approach."}, {"page": 21, "text": "By correlating archaeological, anthropological, toponymic, geological and geomorphic data, Gaillard et al. identified three phases of the pre-1991 13 gro.asan.yrotavresbo.htrae.www"}, {"page": 22, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard eruption: (1) an initial explosive eruption (similar to 1991) that produced a caldera (also similar to the present caldera); (2) the appearance and growth of a dome; and (3) partial collapse of that dome."}, {"page": 22, "text": "Before the Buag eruptions altered the region’s landscape, Manila Bay (or, to be more specific, Pampanga Bay which is the part of Manila Bay closest to the province) extended inland as far as Guagua (about 15 km from the current shoreline).2 The town’s location probably gave it its name (Guagua is Spanish misspelling of the original Uaua, which means “mouth of the river” or “where the river meets the sea”)."}, {"page": 22, "text": "All the present-day towns between Guagua and Manila Bay were underwater, e.g., Macabebe, Sasmuan, Masantol, parts of Lubao and Minalin."}, {"page": 22, "text": "Prehistoric Kapampangan communities dotting the shoreline and riverbanks stretched as far inland as Candaba and Porac."}, {"page": 22, "text": "Archaeological explorations in the two towns have yielded evidence of prehistoric settlement, trading and agriculture, with one site (Babo Balukbuk near the Porac River) showing evidence of tephra fall (airborne debris from a volcanic eruption), which either drove the settlers away or buried them."}, {"page": 22, "text": "The extensive archaeological studies done in this site (by H."}, {"page": 22, "text": "Otley Beyer in 1939, Robert Fox in 1959, Dr."}, {"page": 22, "text": "Victor Paz in 2002) established that (a) different generations of settlers lived on the same site; (b) each generation abandoned the site for the same reason (volcanic activity); and (c) the volcanic activity came in a series within the Buag Eruptive Period."}, {"page": 22, "text": "When Pinatubo erupted 500 to 800 years ago, it ejected a huge ash column that turned day into night like it did in 1991, dumped ash and pumice over a large area, and produced pyroclastic flows that altered the landscape. (The eruption also created a caldera that 14 gro.asan.yrotavresbo.htrae.www Macabebe, Sasmuan and Lubao used to be underwater"}, {"page": 23, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions ArchAeologicAl sites Around PinAtubo In 1939 when anthropologist H."}, {"page": 23, "text": "Otley Beyer unearthed a burial site in Hacienda Ramona dated at least 900 A.D., he declared that Pampanga offered the best field for his next systematic exploration."}, {"page": 23, "text": "In 1959, Robert Fox dug in Balukbuk and discovered a burial jar with a child’s bones and bangles dated 1300 A.D.; in Gubat he unearthed 300 graves dated 1200 A.D. which led him to declare that it was “the most extensive archaeological excavation in the history of the Philippines.” In 2001, the UP Archaeological Studies Program headed by Dr."}, {"page": 23, "text": "Victor Paz and the National Museum’s Archaeology Division headed by Dr."}, {"page": 23, "text": "Eusebio Dizon jointly resumed work on the previous digging sites, and additionally found large quantities of jars, saucers, bronze bangles and burial sites, but no human bones, all buried under a layer of volcanic ash."}, {"page": 23, "text": "They were dated 14th to 16th century, coinciding with the Buag eruption."}, {"page": 23, "text": "All these mean that the Porac highlands were bustling with large settlements, which was unusual because Porac is a good distance from the sea or a major river, which was where early settlers usually put up their communities for livelihood and transportation purposes."}, {"page": 23, "text": "The only possible explanation: the sea was closer to Porac before Pinatubo’s alluvial processes pushed the shoreline away, or the Porac settlers had access to South China Sea through the ancient trails over the mountains at Pinatubo."}, {"page": 23, "text": "According to scientists, a shallow bay existed between the towns of San Felipe in the north and San Antonio and Castillejos in the south, which would have allowed Chinese trading vessels to sail closer to Pinatubo.3 This would also explain the proliferation of Chinese and Vietnamese trade ceramics found in the excavated Porac settlement. 15"}, {"page": 24, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard was as wide as the caldera lake that formed in 1991.) The subsequent rains turned the pyroclastic-flow deposits into lahars, which carried the sediments to the low-lying areas (Guagua), where the silt pushed the shoreline 15 km to where it is today."}, {"page": 24, "text": "Based on sediment study, the Buag lahars filled Sacobia-Bamban River, Abacan River and Pasig-Potrero River but not Porac-Gumain River.4 These events drove populations from areas closest to the volcano (western Pampanga) to areas farthest from the volcano (eastern Pampanga), which was the same resettlement pattern followed by 1991 evacuees.5 Eventually, some of them moved to the delta plain (southern Pampanga) which had been reclaimed by lahar deposition in the initial eruptions, or back to the Porac highlands."}, {"page": 24, "text": "Succeeding eruptions within the same Buag Eruptive Period led to a repeat of the evacuation; by then, evacuees from Porac who wanted to go direct to the reclaimed delta plain had found a shorter route: the ancient Aeta trail from Porac to Lubao through Floridablanca."}, {"page": 24, "text": "By the time Prince Balagtas and his noble kins appeared in Pampanga in c.1380 (some scholars believe they sailed in from the Madjapahit Empire in Java or Borneo), the Buag Eruptive Period was well underway."}, {"page": 24, "text": "Prince Balagtas and wife Panginoan became The ancient the parents of the founders of the ancient towns Kapampangans who founded of Macabebe, Bacolor, Calumpit and Apalit; Apalit, Bacolor a grandson, Pansomun (Fernando Malang and Macabebe Balagtas, who died in 1589) left a will that may have described in great detail the Kapampangan witnessed the territory: it covered a vast area from present- prehistoric day Nueva Vizcaya and Pangasinan to Aurora, eruptions Bulacan, Bataan and Zambales.6 Panginoan’s 16"}, {"page": 25, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions Lines trace the crater of Ancestral Pinatubo (outer) and the pre-1991 eruption crater (inner), forming concentric circles around the 1991 crater, as seen from a satellite. big volcAnoes, smAll volcAnoes The size of volcanoes is usually not a good indicator of its eruptive power."}, {"page": 25, "text": "Huge, fully formed volcanoes like Mount Mayon and Mount Fuji usually produce weak eruptions, which allow rock, ash and other debris to pile up around the crater and form a conical peak."}, {"page": 25, "text": "The most violent volcanoes are often the least visible volcanoes, because they explode and create a huge hole and then collapse on top of it."}, {"page": 25, "text": "Some calderas (like the Yellowstone crater) are so huge that the complete circular outline can only be detected from a satellite."}, {"page": 25, "text": "The diminishing size of ancestral and modern Pinatubo can be seen on satellite photographs as traces of concentric circles around the present caldera. brother Salalila was the parent of the rulers of Tondo and Manila (Lakan Dula, Rajah Matanda and probably Rajah Soliman)."}, {"page": 25, "text": "It was this Kapampangan-Tagalog family alliance which established and ruled the area around the bay and from which descended people with such surnames as Gatbonton, Macapagal, Gatchalian, Gatmaitan, Gatdula, Musngi, Lumanlan, Capulong, Soliman and Lakandula."}, {"page": 25, "text": "These prehistoric Kapampangans and Tagalogs were probably not even aware that Pinatubo was slowly filling up the caldera with a lava dome, because the process was not as violent as the initial eruption and was confined only to the summit area."}, {"page": 25, "text": "It was most likely the Aetas living around the volcano that witnessed the dome- building activity, and it was probably they who named the mountain 17"}, {"page": 26, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard accordingly (pinatubo, “made to grow”)."}, {"page": 26, "text": "By the time the Buag Eruptive Period ended, Pinatubo had a steep-sided dome which gave it the conical shape that everybody saw prior to the 1991 eruption."}, {"page": 26, "text": "At some point in the dome-building activity, Dr."}, {"page": 26, "text": "Gaillard says, a portion of the dome collapsed, remobilizing pyroclastic-flow deposits towards the upper Marella and Santo Tomas river valleys on the Zambales side."}, {"page": 26, "text": "The rampaging currents of volcanic debris buried a trading community in Buag (where archaeologists later dug up old chinaware)."}, {"page": 26, "text": "This is probably the reason the place was given a name that means “collapse.”7 When the Spaniards arrived in Manila and Pampanga in 1571, Pinatubo had long quieted down, allowing communities along the riverbanks to thrive."}, {"page": 26, "text": "Thus, Betis and Lubao were described by Spanish chroniclers as heavily populated settlements, and Manila as a city protected by palisades."}, {"page": 26, "text": "The Tagalog-Kapampangan alliance ended when the rulers of Manila and Tondo (Rajah Matanda, Rajah Soliman and Lakan Dula) welcomed the colonizers, while “the brave youth from Macabebe” (Tarik Soliman) put up a fierce resistance until death."}, {"page": 26, "text": "The Spaniards missed even the tail end of the Buag Eruptive Period, which was why they never referred to Pinatubo as a volcano throughout their 300-year stay in the colony. 1Gaillard, Jean-Christophe, Delfin Jr, F G, Dizon, E.Z., Paz, V.J, Ramos, E.G., Remotigue, C.T., Rodolfo, K.S., Siringan, F., Soria, J.L.A., Umbal, J.V., A reconstruction of the ca. 800-500 BP."}, {"page": 26, "text": "Henson, The Province of Pampanga and its Towns A.D. 1300-1962 (Unpublished). 7Gaillard et al. 18"}, {"page": 27, "text": "THE AETAS kNEW An old Aeta legend tells of a giant turtle throwing rocks, mud and dust from a hole on the mountain, with fire coming out of its mouth The ancestors of Aetas—arguably the first people in the Philippines—came to the archipelago allegedly by a land bridge that connected southern China, Taiwan and northern Luzon about 30,000 years ago."}, {"page": 27, "text": "They lived on the plains of Luzon until the sea- faring Austronesians arrived and occupied the plains on both sides of Pinatubo."}, {"page": 27, "text": "The brown-skinned Austronesians on the eastern side became the Kapampangans; those on the western side became the Sambals (from Sambali, the old name of Zambales)."}, {"page": 27, "text": "The dark-skinned Aetas retreated to the foothills of Pinatubo."}, {"page": 27, "text": "It was they who named the mountain Pinatubo (root word tubo, “to grow” or “to originate from”) which, according to a 1952 article in The Philippine Journal of Science by ethnographer Robert B."}, {"page": 27, "text": "Fox, referred to the mountain being the origin of all the life-giving rivers in the forests. 19 sudoxE dna noitpurE"}, {"page": 28, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Robert B."}, {"page": 28, "text": "Fox’s 1947 map of Pinatubo Negrito territory at the Maraunot river valley."}, {"page": 28, "text": "Although Aetas roamed practically the whole Zambales Mountain Range, it was in the Pinatubo area where the most number of Aetas settled because of the numerous rivers flowing from the volcano."}, {"page": 28, "text": "They crossed over to Tarlac and Pampanga through the Capas Trail, probably the same route taken by Kapampangans going to Zambales."}, {"page": 28, "text": "Botolan, named after the seedy banana butulan, is said to have been founded by a Doña Teresa of Mabalacat in 1819. 20 4-3 .soN 18 .loV ecneicS fo lanruoJ enippilihP ehT"}, {"page": 29, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions Fox cited the Aetas’ frequent use of plants not found in the hinterlands but in the mountains’ lower altitude as one evidence that they were not originally mountain dwellers.1 He also reported finding, in 1947, an extensive porcelain site in the unlikeliest of places, deep in Negrito territory on Pinatubo’s west side, near Ugik."}, {"page": 29, "text": "The porcelain pieces discovered there were identified as 13th- to 15th-century Yuan and Early Ming Negrito boy with chipped wares."}, {"page": 29, "text": "Indeed, the Mount Pinatubo area incisors which gave rise to rumored sightings of savage was once close enough to the sea to permit Aetas in the Pinatubo area."}, {"page": 29, "text": "They maritime traders to penetrate even Negrito supposedly perished in a cave during the eruption."}, {"page": 29, "text": "And since tribe, the so-called Aburlin this area had a direct link to the east side pagans, refused to evacuate during the eruption and were via the so-called Capas Trail (a natural never heard from again. pass through the Zambales Mountain Range), whatever was brought in from South China Sea was easily transported to Tarlac and northern Pampanga (including Porac), and vice versa."}, {"page": 29, "text": "One evidence that Sambals and Aetas regularly crossed over to the other side (through the Capas Trail) was the high incidence of raids and ambuscades they committed on residents and travellers in Tarlac and Pampanga."}, {"page": 29, "text": "On the other hand, one evidence that Kapampangans crossed over to Zambales was the fact that the town of Botolan was founded in 1819 by a group led by a Doña Teresa of Mabalacat, according to historian Alex Castro."}, {"page": 29, "text": "The Capas Trail actually led directly to Botolan."}, {"page": 29, "text": "Throughout the Spanish colonial period, Aetas attempted to occupy land on the western fringes of Pampanga."}, {"page": 29, "text": "The town of Mabalacat used to be an Aeta community ruled by a chieftain named Caragan."}, {"page": 29, "text": "Culiat, a forested area north of San Fernando, was also occupied by Aetas until Angel Pantaleon de Miranda developed it into a town named Angeles."}, {"page": 29, "text": "Aetas were often held in captivity and sold as slaves by both Sambals and Kapampangans.2 Unlike Sambals and Kapampangans, Aetas resisted the lifestyle change that the colonizers tried to impose on them."}, {"page": 29, "text": "For example, when the Spaniards made an attempt to confine them to pueblos, Aetas relocated deeper into 21 4-3 .soN 18 .loV ecneicS fo lanruoJ enippilihP"}, {"page": 30, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard the Pinatubo forests where they could roam freely, making only occasional forays to low-lying villages to sell their catch (birds, deer, freshwater eels), raid houses, and ambush solitary travelers."}, {"page": 30, "text": "Their stay in the mountains eventually turned them into hunter- gatherers."}, {"page": 30, "text": "As animists, Aetas then as now believe in spirits inhabiting rocks, trees, plants, and mountains."}, {"page": 30, "text": "They worship a supreme being (Namalyari), whom they believe to be residing at the summit or inside Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 30, "text": "They have no concept of the linear passage of time, mixing up past and present events when they narrate a story or experience."}, {"page": 30, "text": "They also do not count years accurately; a septuagenarian could claim that he is over a hundred years old."}, {"page": 30, "text": "Aetas do not have a counterpart myth to the Kapampangans’ legendary war between Sinukuan and Namalyari, but a 1915 document collected by Prof."}, {"page": 30, "text": "Otley Beyer contains a narrative entitled The Origin of Pinatubu Volcano (A Negrito Myth) which describes a battle between spirits: Blit, whose brother is Wasi, “the spirit of the wind,” joins Aglao, “king of the spirit “Rocks, mud, dust and hunters” in the pursuit of a giant turtle named other things began Bacobaco, “the spirit of the sea.” The details to fall in showers all of the battle bear an uncanny resemblance to around the mountain. volcanic activity."}, {"page": 30, "text": "Bacobaco howled In the story, Bacobaco tried to hide in a lake and howled so loudly at the foot of Mount Pinatubo, but finding the that the earth shook. water clear, he climbed to the peak where he The fire that escaped started digging a hole. from his mouth became so thick “Bit pieces of rock, mud, dust and other things and so hot that the began to fall in showers all around the mountain. pursuing party had During all the while, (Bacobaco) howled and to run away.” howled so loudly that the earth shook under the Negrito Myth,1915 foot of Blit, Aglao and his hosts."}, {"page": 31, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions escaped from his mouth became so thick and so hot that the pursuing party had to run away.” “For three days,” the story goes, “the turtle continued to burrow itself, throwing rocks, muds, ashes and thundering away all the 1904 photograph shows unusual rock formations in Sta."}, {"page": 31, "text": "Fe, Zambales, along the Mapanuepe River, which time in deafening wars. may be prehistoric pyroclastic-flow deposits."}, {"page": 31, "text": "At the end of the three days he stopped, and all was quiet again in the mountain."}, {"page": 31, "text": "But the lake, with its clear water, was now filled with rocks, and mud covered everything."}, {"page": 31, "text": "On the summit of Pinatubu was a great hole, through which Bacobaco had passed, and from which smoke could be seen constantly coming out."}, {"page": 31, "text": "This showed that although he was already quiet, he was still full of anger, since fire continued to come from his mouth.” The story ends on an ominous note: “But now, you do not see the smoke coming out of the Pinatubu mountain any longer, and many believe that the terrible monster is already dead."}, {"page": 31, "text": "But I think that he is just resting after his exertions, and that someday he will surely come out of his hiding place again for a hearty meal on deer, and then, woe be to us!” This 1915 document is remarkable because (a) the description of Bacobaco’s escape reads almost like a textbook description of volcanic eruption (smoking crater hole, earthquakes and mudflows, rain of ash, dust, mud and rocks); (b) it shows how the Aetas’ collective memory of the last eruption (c.1491) has persisted until the 20th century; and (c) the Aetas know Pinatubo is an active volcano which can erupt again."}, {"page": 31, "text": "The title of the 1915 document itself, The Origin of Pinatubu Volcano, indicates that the Aetas and maybe the Americans or Kapampangans who documented the story had an idea of the volcanic nature of Pinatubo--handed down to them through oral tradition, or deduced from the presence of hot springs and sulfuric steams on the flanks of the mountain. 1Hiromu Shimizu, Pinatubo Aytas: Continuity and Change (Ateneo de Manila, 1989), p. 6. 2 Ibid., p. 12. 23 )selabmaZ fo sotirgeN( deeR nallA mailliW"}, {"page": 32, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard cAPAs trAil And the lost kingdom of sAnfotsi Prehistoric people on both sides of Pinatubo regularly crossed over and traded with each other through gaps between the mountains The name Luzon appears in this 1593 Chinese illustration of the easten sea (Dongyang), to which Luzon belonged, and the eastern sea (Xiyang)."}, {"page": 32, "text": "Contrary to what most people think, the Zambales Mountain Range is not an impenetrable barrier between the Zambales-Bataan area (west side of Pinatubo) and the Pampanga-Tarlac area (east side)."}, {"page": 32, "text": "People from either side crossed over quite often and freely, not by climbing to the top and then descending to the other side, but by simply using the natural passes or gaps between the mountains."}, {"page": 32, "text": "It was used by prehistoric inhabitants (Kapampangans, Sambals and even Aetas) as a trade route between ports on Zambales’ coast and the old Kapampangan territory, which was teeming with communities even long before the Spaniards came."}, {"page": 32, "text": "This explains the discovery of prehistoric chinaware in unlikely places like Porac and Candaba—unlikely because the two towns are located a good distance from the Pampanga river delta (Macabebe 24 spaM esenihC tneicnA ni senippilihP ehT"}, {"page": 33, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions and Lubao), the logical trading post due to its proximity to a strategic bay (Manila Bay)."}, {"page": 33, "text": "A Chinese chronicler, Chao Ju-Kua (1170-1231) wrote about the kingdom of Sanfotsi, which was located somewhere near Sumatra, Java and Malaysia, with a port named Lingyamon (Lingayen?), where most people were surnamed Pu (Apu?), and where the capital was populated by people “scattered outside the city, or on the water on rafts of boards covered over with reeds” who were “skilled at fighting on land and water."}, {"page": 33, "text": "In facing the enemy and braving death they have no equal among other nations."}, {"page": 33, "text": "During most of the year the climate is hot and there is but little cold weather."}, {"page": 33, "text": "Their domestic animals are very much like those of China."}, {"page": 33, "text": "They have wine made from flowers, Male and female inhabitants of Luzon as depicted in the book Huang Qing Zhi Gong Tu, about 17th century wine from coconuts, wine from areca nuts and honey, all fermented.” Scholars like Roland Braddell and Paul Wheatley think Sanfotsi was part of Northern Borneo, but according to J.L."}, {"page": 33, "text": "Denis and Austin Craig, Sanfotsi was located in the Philippines."}, {"page": 33, "text": "Even Muslim chroniclers mention the place."}, {"page": 33, "text": "According to Abu Zayd, the ruler of Sanfotsi lived in a city located in an “estuary resembling the Tigris River (which) brings in salt water during the high tide and sweet water during the low tide.” It faced the southern coast of China."}, {"page": 33, "text": "If Lingayen was indeed the port of Sanfotsi, the nearest delta area would be Pampanga which was, indeed, a busy trading post in prehistoric times."}, {"page": 33, "text": "Its river systems, particularly the Rio Grande and Rio Chico, allowed traders to go farther north, as far as Candaba 25 spaM esenihC tneicnA ni senippilihP ehT"}, {"page": 34, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard and even Nueva Ecija and Pangasinan, thus raising the possibility of the whole Pampanga River Basin being a region of flourishing trade."}, {"page": 34, "text": "When the Spaniards came, they made the whole region the Provincia de la Pampanga."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Another Chinese chronicler, Zhang Xie (1574-1640), mentioned a place called He-mao-li (Mauli?"}, {"page": 34, "text": "The Kapampangan word for “going south” is mauli, i.e., the Macabebe area, according to scholar Joel Mallari), “an excellent land for so small a country,” which was “neighbor to Lu-song” (Luzon?) whose “famous sight was Mount Luo-hang, topped with white stone” (White Rock of Mount Arayat? ash-capped Mount Pinatubo?)."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Chao Ju-Kua also mentioned the Hay-tan (Aetas) who lived in a place of “many lofty hills and rugged rocks which rise up like gigantic walls (and who) ascend the mountain with the same ease as if they were on the level.” These pygmies “wander through the fastness of the thickets and invisible to the sight, shoot their arrows at the passers-by."}, {"page": 34, "text": "On this account they are greatly feared."}, {"page": 34, "text": "When the trader presents them a porcelain jar, they bow and take it, and then uttering cries of joy, run away with it.” If Sanfotsi was indeed in central Luzon, the Lingayen-Macabebe connection would be augmented by west to east access (Zambales to Tarlac) through the Capas Trail."}, {"page": 34, "text": "The discovery of tradeware ceramics, an old boat hull and stone anchors in the Maraunot river valley bolsters this theory."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Mallari also says that the discovery of 13th-century ceramics in Lubao lends credence to the theory that inhabitants of the Porac settlement, bringing their valuables (e.g. porcelain) with them, always fled to, and resettled in, Lubao every time Pinatubo erupted, using the ancient Aeta trails through the highlands of Floridablanca."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Mallari likewise theorizes that the evacuees from Porac may have reached as far as old Sta."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Ana (Manila) and Calatagan, Batangas—two areas where archaeologists have unearthed sherds of grey-buff (ashen) earthenware that could have come only from the prehistoric Porac settlement where pot-makers used ash deposits for their unique products."}, {"page": 34, "text": "The Buag Eruptive Period in c.1491 halted the trading activities around Pinatubo."}, {"page": 34, "text": "The date corresponds with the time the word Sanfotsi dropped out of sight from Chinese historical records."}, {"page": 34, "text": "References: http://sambali.blogspot.com/2006/07/sambali-glossary.html Chao Ju-Kua’s Description of the Philippines in Blair and Robertson’s The Philippine Islands 1493-1898."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Main, Dorothy (1982) The Calatagan earthenwares : a description of pottery complexes excavated in Batangas Province, Philippines /; with “notes on the comparisons and relationships of the Calatagan earthenwares with other prehistoric potteries of the Philippines” by Robert B."}, {"page": 35, "text": "dUEllING dEITIES Our ancestors considered the area between the two mystical mountains the center of the world Mount Pinatubo shaped the land of the Kapampangans, while the mountain on the other side, Mount Arayat, shaped their culture and history."}, {"page": 35, "text": "The reason their sea-faring ancestors came to Pampanga was that they were attracted to Mount Arayat, which is visible from Manila Bay."}, {"page": 35, "text": "They first found their sacred river, the Rio Grande, which led them to their sacred mountain (Arayat)."}, {"page": 35, "text": "Mount Arayat served as battleground between Spaniards and revolutionaries, between Americans and insurrects, between Japanese soldiers and the Huks, between government forces and insurgents."}, {"page": 35, "text": "Throughout history, it has provided refuge to scoundrels and fugitives, sanctuary to mystics and cultists, and adventure to mountaineers and plain thrill-seekers. 27 moc.sserpdrow.olrac"}, {"page": 36, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard To the Kapampangan common folk who live intimately around it, Mount Arayat is a looming presence that populates their dreams and nightmares, and fires their imagination."}, {"page": 36, "text": "This most recognizable geographical and cultural icon has generated more legends and myths than any other object or event in the region has."}, {"page": 36, "text": "One such legend is about Kargon-Kargon, the giant who scooped up a mountain from Candaba and transplanted it to Arayat town, leaving behind what we now know as the Candaba Swamp."}, {"page": 36, "text": "He had a son, Suku, who lived in a white palace on the mountaintop with his three daughters."}, {"page": 36, "text": "Suku’s name means “old” not “surrender,” as some might think."}, {"page": 36, "text": "Many Kapampangans still refer to the mountain as Mount Sinukuan, although it is officially called Mount Arayat, after the town of its location."}, {"page": 36, "text": "In the legend, Suku had a friend named Namalyari who lived in the mountain across the plain."}, {"page": 36, "text": "Their friendship ended after the latter proposed marriage to Suku’s daughter Maria (also known as Mariang Sinukuan)."}, {"page": 36, "text": "The two giants got into a rock-throwing fight, with Suku beating Namalyari and then cutting Namalyari’s mountain in half.1 Some might draw a connection between the legend and the fact that Pinatubo used to be a huge mountain until a prehistoric eruption also cut it in half."}, {"page": 36, "text": "The Austronesians who came from southern China on boats called balangays about 4500 B.P. barely missed Pinatubo’s Crow Valley Eruptive Period (6000-5000 B.P.)."}, {"page": 36, "text": "By then, Mount Arayat had been quite dormant (its last eruption occurred between 650,000 and 530,000 B.P.).2 Most of these Austronesian seafarers only made the archipelago their stopover; they proceeded to Indonesia and the outlying Pacific islands."}, {"page": 36, "text": "Those who stayed behind became our ancestors, the future Kapampangans (and other Filipinos). (The Aetas, by comparison, arrived in the Philippines much earlier, about 25,000 years before the Austronesians did.) According to geologists, Arayat’s last explosive eruptions occurred on the western flank of the volcano (that’s the slope facing Pampanga)."}, {"page": 36, "text": "Besides ash fall, these eruptions triggered massive pyroclastic flows, base surges and lava, including a huge avalanche that created what looks like an amphitheatre at the top of the mountain.3 When it was over, the lava dome protruded on the slope—a quite conspicuous white rock that led our ancestors to imagine the palace of Sinukuan. 28"}, {"page": 37, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions Because geologists have found no prehistoric lahar deposits around the mountain, they concluded that Mount Arayat is a Strombolian volcano (the type that produces small lava flows), not Plinian (the type that produces a lot of pyroclastic materials, like Mount Pinatubo)."}, {"page": 37, "text": "The latter generates catastrophic explosive eruptions."}, {"page": 37, "text": "It was actually the Aetas who named the Pinatubo deity Apu Namalyari, “lord who can make anything possible.” The early Kapampangans had a different name for him: Apu Punsalan, which means “lord of enmity.” With a name like that, the stage was set for the cosmic battle between the Zeus-type patrician god on Mount Arayat and the belligerent god on Mount Pinatubo. “The two giants saw each other and in an instant huge stones were hurled against one another."}, {"page": 37, "text": "The battle lasted two days and the opponent of Suku was beaten,” went one version of the story, recorded by a student of H."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Nicdao wrote that Mount Zambales was once “the greatest mountain in the archipelago,” but “The two giants after the battle “it was shattered into fragments hurled huge stones and today we see a range of mountains called at each other."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Zambales Range.”4 The battle raged Another version of the Sinukuan-Namalyari for two days, and feud appeared in Dean S."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Fansler’s collection the enemy of Suku Filipino Popular Tales (1921)."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Mount Zambales, Fansler got from Kapampangan sources, Bathala once a huge had a son, Apolaqui and a daughter, Mayari mountain, (Namalyari). was shattered into “From the eyes of these children the earth fragments and received its first light,” the story went."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Bathala became a loved his children, but they were too preoccupied mountain range.” with their selfish pursuits."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Otley Beyer Collections left no will to them."}, {"page": 37, "text": "Apolaqui wanted to rule all (1916) 29 irallaM leoJ"}, {"page": 38, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard the earth without leaving anything for his sister, and a feud developed between the two. “For a long time they fought with bamboo clubs,” the story continued."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Apolaqui struck Mayari in the face which made her lose one eye."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Feeling guilty, Apolaqui vowed to share power with his sister."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Thus Apolaqui became the Sun who ruled the earth during the day, while Mayari became the Moon who ruled during the night."}, {"page": 38, "text": "With only one eye left, she had a fainter light than her brother."}, {"page": 38, "text": "What prompted the ancient Kapampangans to weave a story about two feuding mountains?"}, {"page": 38, "text": "How were they able to pick out Mount Pinatubo from among the other peaks in the mountain range and position it as Mount Arayat’s match?"}, {"page": 38, "text": "If they witnessed a prehistoric eruption of Pinatubo, surely they could not have seen a prehistoric eruption of Arayat, the last of which occurred half a million years ago when the region was still uninhabited."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Some scholars see the battle between the Kapampangans’ Sinukuan and the Aetas’ Namalyari as a metaphor for the skirmishes that frequently erupted between lowlanders (Kapampangans) and highlanders (Aetas), mostly as a result of the latter’s ambuscades and raids on the former’s property."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Namalyari’s defeat in the hands of Sinukuan likewise mirrors the Aetas’ subjugation and flight to the hills."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Other scholars say our ancestors had two geographical centers, northern Pampanga which It was a fight is between Pinatubo and Arayat, and southern between the Zeus- Pampanga, which is where the Pampanga River type patrician god empties into the sea. (Early Kapampangans Sinukuan and the in the river delta area used the word paralaya belligerent god to mean “going upstream, towards Arayat Punsalan, otherwise or eastward,” and paroba to mean “going in known as Namalyari the opposite direction, i.e., downstream or 30"}, {"page": 39, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions westward towards Pinatubo.”) Fansler’s story of Apolaqui (Arayat) being the Sun and Mayari (Pinatubo) being the Moon was only the Kapampangan version—one of many from other regions and countries—of the universal theme of the enmity between Sun and Moon."}, {"page": 39, "text": "Even Sinukuan’s children had day-related names like Munag Sumala (Dawn) and Ugtu (Noon), while a child of Namalyari was appropriately named Sisilim (Twilight).5 In a legend common among the fisherfolk of Masantol, the supreme god Mangatia (Net Weaver) created the sky as a great canopy of fishing net studded with stars."}, {"page": 39, "text": "When he was done, he dropped the sewing needle which became the white rock (Piedra Blanca) on Mount Arayat--the spot, legend says, where the magical entrance to Sinukuan’s subterranean palace is located.6 A variation of the Sinukuan-Namalyari feud was found by scholar Paul Kekai Manansala in The Headhunters of Northern Luzon, a work by U.S."}, {"page": 39, "text": "Army officer and scholar, Cornelis DeWitt Willcox (1861-1938)."}, {"page": 39, "text": "A passage reads: “According to the native legend, this mountain (Arayat) used to form part of the Zambales range."}, {"page": 39, "text": "It became, however, by reason of its quarrelsome disposition, so objectionable to its neighbors of this range, that they finally resolved no longer to endure its cantankerous nature and accordingly banished it to its present position in the plain of Central Luzon, where it would have 31 seraneH navI The Kapampangans’ sacred mountain, Arayat, and their sacred river, the Rio Grande."}, {"page": 39, "text": "The Candaba Swamp, where Sinukuan uprooted the mountain, lies nearby."}, {"page": 40, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard between the devil And the deeP blue seA Every time Mount Pinatubo erupts, pyroclastic flows spread out in all directions, but mostly towards Zambales on the west side and Pampanga on the east."}, {"page": 40, "text": "The difference between the two is that in Zambales, the volcanic debris is free to go to the sea through relatively wide and straight river channels, while in Pampanga, the debris must inch its way through a complex network of rivers and populated areas before reaching Manila Bay."}, {"page": 40, "text": "Much of the debris loses momentum along the way and gets stuck as silt."}, {"page": 40, "text": "The added weight of Pinatubo sediments on Pampanga worsens a condition called subsidence, in which the land compresses and sinks under its own weight."}, {"page": 40, "text": "To understand this, we have to look at the Pampanga River Basin as Central Luzon’s drainage system, i.e., rivers from Nueva Vizcaya, Pangasinan, Nueva Ecija, Tarlac and Pampanga collect into the Pampanga River as it heads towards Manila Bay."}, {"page": 40, "text": "Pampanga is in the spot where all the collected water from Central Luzon, as well as sediments from Pinatubo, empty into the bay."}, {"page": 40, "text": "In fact, much of the province sits precariously on silt that has only recently reclaimed the sea."}, {"page": 40, "text": "When the province becomes too heavy for its own good, subsidence occurs."}, {"page": 40, "text": "Too much extraction of underground water by artesian wells and pumps likewise depletes the water bed and contributes to subsidence.1 And when the land sinks below sea level, seawater will come rushing in."}, {"page": 40, "text": "One proof that subsidence is already happening is that the floods in the province are more frequent and stay longer."}, {"page": 40, "text": "According to scientists, the province will sink deeply enough to let the sea in, submerging first the towns of Sasmuan and Lubao (the ancient Pampanga Bay) and possibly Masantol and Macabebe, then Guagua, Bacolor and Minalin."}, {"page": 40, "text": "If Pampanga eventually sinks into Manila Bay, Kapampangans can take comfort in the certainty that it will rise again, thanks to Pinatubo’s lahars which will reclaim it."}, {"page": 40, "text": "There is evidence that Pampanga had sunk and had been reclaimed before, not once, not twice, but maybe several times, as many times as Pinatubo had erupted."}, {"page": 40, "text": "The prehistoric marine materials unearthed in the Guagua-Bacolor area show that the sea used to be much farther inland."}, {"page": 40, "text": "The large prehistoric settlement excavated in the Porac highlands shows that the sea probably extended all the way to the foothills of Pinatubo where the Porac settlement was found; otherwise why would the prehistoric settlers build their large community high up in the mountain where there was no body of water close by?2 1 Dr."}, {"page": 40, "text": "Fernando Siringan, “Net Sea Level Change in the Pampanga Delta Region: Causes and Consequences,” lecture delivered at the Center for Kapampangan Studies in August, 2003. 2 Dr."}, {"page": 40, "text": "Victor Paz, “First Conclusions of the April 2002 Archaeological Excavations in Porac,” lecture delivered at the Center for Kapampangan Studies in August 2003. 32"}, {"page": 41, "text": "The Prehistoric Eruptions no neighbors to annoy, and where it has stood ever since, rising solitary from the surrounding plain.”7 This version bears a similarity to another Sinukuan legend told to Don Pedro Serrano by an octogenarian informant in 1889, as contained in Isabelo de los Reyes’ anthology El Folklore Filipino."}, {"page": 41, "text": "The octogenarian, he said, had also heard the story as a boy from another old man who allegedly “was the only one who managed to penetrate even the farthest corners of that big mountain, because he was a friend of the sorcerer Suku (the Invincible) who resided there.”8 In Serrano’s version, Sinukuan left his wife Mingan to live in a hill that was surrounded by high mountains."}, {"page": 41, "text": "His presence made the hill grow into a mountain, until it outgrew the surrounding mountains."}, {"page": 41, "text": "Instead of Sinukuan’s mountain leaving the other mountains, it was the other mountains which left Arayat."}, {"page": 41, "text": "The Kapampangan tale of Kargon-Kargon (Sinukuan’s father, who created the Candaba Swamp after scooping up and transplanting Mount Arayat) had a Sambal version, as told to Abraham Anonas of Masinloc, Zambales, in the 1970s."}, {"page": 41, "text": "In the story, a magician granted a local ruler’s wish to access a mountain where he could hunt again like he did in his youth, by planting a magic stone in the plain which grew into Mount In Masantol folklore, Pinatubo."}, {"page": 41, "text": "The ruler rewarded the magician the supreme being with the hand of his daughter, Alindaya, who Mangatia wove a was quite unhappy with the arrangement. great canopy of Her refusal angered the magician who let the fishing net studded mountain grow so big it overwhelmed the with stars, then region."}, {"page": 41, "text": "A noble prince came to the rescue by dropped his sewing uprooting the mountain and transplanting it to needle which became where it is today."}, {"page": 41, "text": "It left behind a lake which the White Rock on came to be known as Lake Andaya."}, {"page": 42, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Manansala found another folk tale mentioning a “cloud bridge” that connected the two mountains."}, {"page": 42, "text": "He said this “bridge” might be an allusion to a ridge between Arayat and Pinatubo—a topographic anomaly mentioned by a colonial-era geologist, Richard von Drasche- Wartinberg (1850-1923) in his article “The volcanic region around Manila” (1876)."}, {"page": 42, "text": "The Austrian geologist climbed to the top of Mount Arayat and observed the meandering rivers in Pampanga and Tarlac."}, {"page": 42, "text": "He wrote, “If one were to draw a line from Monte Pinatubo to the isolated mountain of Arayat in the plain, one would notice that all the rivers north of this line flow in a northeasterly direction, while all those south of it flow in a southeasterly direction toward Rio Grande de la Pampanga."}, {"page": 42, "text": "This circumstance may be observed particularly plainly from the top of the Arayat, where I first noticed this slope of the plain in both directions, increasing toward Monte Pinatubo."}, {"page": 42, "text": "East of Monte Arayat this circumstance disappears entirely.”8 The simple explanation would be Pinatubo’s pyroclastic-flow deposits fanning out towards Arayat, in effect pushing aside the rivers flowing out of Pinatubo."}, {"page": 42, "text": "The rivers north of these deposits, i.e., Abacan, Sacobia and O’Donnell, would naturally flow in a northeasterly direction, but as soon as they reach the plain, they follow the land’s natural gradient and flow southward towards Manila Bay. 1 Mount Pinatubo is actually higher than Mount Arayat: prior to the 1991 eruption, it rose to 5725 ft. compared to Arayat’s 3366 ft."}, {"page": 42, "text": "After the eruption, it went down to 4872 ft., still higher than Arayat. 2 Gaillard, Singsing Magazine Vol. 1 No.3, p.10. 3 Ibid. 4 H."}, {"page": 42, "text": "Otley Beyer, Philippine Folklore, Social Customs and Beliefs (A Collection of Original Sources), Vol. 9 (Manila: 1918), unpublished. 5 Paul Kekai Manansala, Quests of the Dragon and Bird Clan (October 10, 2009) (www. sambali.blogspot.com). 6 Ibid. 7 Ibid. 8 Don Pedro Serrano and Edilberto V."}, {"page": 45, "text": "Pinatubo’s cool air and panoramic view of 1571 - 1946 South China Sea and Central Luzon invited Idyllic the colonizers to build settlements on its slopes such as Camp Sanchez, located on Hideaway a plateau near the summit. (Sketch by a member of the 24th Cavalry of the U.S."}, {"page": 47, "text": "ClUElESS COlONIzERS 1571 - 1946 Spain made a town near Pinatubo the capital of the Philippines, while the United States set up its largest offshore military base at the foothills of the volcano The Spaniards who occupied Pampanga for 300 years had no idea that a volcano lurked around the corner."}, {"page": 47, "text": "They made Bacolor, a town only a few kilometers from Pinatubo, the capital of the Philippines in 1762-64, during the British Occupation of Manila."}, {"page": 47, "text": "They established their largest air base on the immediate east side of Pinatubo and their largest naval base on the west side."}, {"page": 47, "text": "If Pinatubo’s last prehistoric eruption occurred approximately 500 years ago, that would be about 1491—practically the eve of the Spanish Conquest."}, {"page": 47, "text": "Ferdinand Magellan landed in Cebu 30 years later in 1521 while Miguel Lopez de Legazpi and his conquistadores sailed into Manila Bay 50 years thereafter in 1571."}, {"page": 48, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard An 1832 map of Pampanga shows the intricate web of river channels emanating from Pinatubo, which the map does not identify. to penetrate Pampanga through the Rio Grande (Pampanga River)."}, {"page": 48, "text": "The Pampanga that the Spaniards saw was heavily populated in the southern parts: Betis had 7000 inhabitants, Macabebe 2600 and Candaba 2000.1 Were they evacuees from the northern towns devastated by the eruption?"}, {"page": 48, "text": "The Porac settlements dug up by archaeologists bear evidence that they were hastily abandoned about the time of the eruptions."}, {"page": 48, "text": "The evacuating inhabitants of Porac most likely avoided the rampaging lahars along The Bacolor cemetery Pasig-Potrero, Abacan and Gumain rivers chapel in c.1901 and used ancient trails through Floridablanca leading directly to Lubao and the coastal areas."}, {"page": 48, "text": "Porac inhabitants There they must have encountered the early fleeing the eruption Moro settlers. used the ancient Aeta trails to As the Spaniards sailed farther upstream, Lubao through they found increasingly sparse populations, Floridablanca due as much to the thicker vegetation and 40 ecluD led sodazlaC sonitsugA serdaP sol ed lautiripsE noicartsinimdA 3381 ,sanipiliF salsI sal ed suseJ ed erbmoN"}, {"page": 49, "text": "Pinatubo in Colonial Times volcAno clues in old dictionAries Take a look at two curious words in Fray Diego Bergaño’s 1732 Kapampangan dictionary: tubu, “to grow or increase, like a mountain” and buga, “a white and spongy stone.” How would early Kapampangans know that a mountain could increase its size, unless they had seen an erupting, dome-building volcano?"}, {"page": 49, "text": "And why would they make the word for pumice stone synonymous to “to throw”?"}, {"page": 49, "text": "Although tubu is just a phonetic variation of the similar Tagalog and Sambal tubo (“to grow”), we can rule out a Kapampangan origin for the name Pinatubo."}, {"page": 49, "text": "The word pinatubo (“made to grow or increase”) is Sambal, not Kapampangan, conjugation."}, {"page": 49, "text": "The Kapampangan equivalent of Pinatubo is pepatubu or petubu."}, {"page": 49, "text": "The word could refer either to the volcano’s dome growth, which Aetas most likely witnessed during the Buag Eruptive Period, or to their crop-raising activities on the slopes of the volcano."}, {"page": 49, "text": "Forman’s 1971 Kapampangan dictionary also has a curious entry: margaha, “volcanic ash.”1 The word should not be in a Kapampangan dictionary because the /h/ sound is not part of the language, and because Kapampangans in 1971 had no basis for coining such a word. 1 Gaillard, J-C, Delfin Jr, F G, Dizon, E.Z., Paz, V.J, Ramos, E.G., Remotigue, C.T., Rodolfo, K.S., Siringan, F., Soria, J.L.A., Umbal, J.V., A reconstruction of the ca. 800- 500 BP."}, {"page": 49, "text": "Pinatubo, Philippines (forthcoming). presence of headhunting tribes as to the areas’ proximity to a recently active volcano."}, {"page": 49, "text": "Although it had been more or less 80 years since the last major eruption, Pinatubo’s eruptive pattern shows the volcano’s dome-building activities and lahar flows continuing for years and probably decades, so it is possible that the conquistadores witnessed the waning phase of the Buag Eruptive Period or at least experienced its after-effects."}, {"page": 49, "text": "Had the Spanish chroniclers been sharper, they would have found out that the reason one community was called Bakulud (Bacolor today) was that it used to be flatland until lahars elevated it (makabakulud means “elevated land” in ancient Kapampangan); or that Uaua (Guagua today) used to be the mouth of a river, until lahars pushed the shoreline to where it was during the Conquest, Sasmuan and Macabebe. 41"}, {"page": 50, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard PinAtubo, 1680 One of the few colonial-era documents that mention Pinatubo by name is actually the earliest: Relation of the Zambals (1680) by Dominican missionary Fray Domingo Perez."}, {"page": 50, "text": "A passage reads: “The road is over sandy ground which is very large and full of rocks left by the river which flows from the mountain of Pinatuba (sic); and in those places where there are no rocks, but only the sand, the road is also very wearisome because that sand has no cohesion, and the least wind that blows lifts the dust which blinds the travelers and has thus cost the greatest hardship to those of this district who take that road in going and coming between the village and the mountain.”1 1 Emma Blair and James Robertson, The Philippine Islands 1493-1803 (1903: Cleveland, Ohio)."}, {"page": 50, "text": "Most colonial-era references to volcanic debris from Pinatubo do not mention Pinatubo by name."}, {"page": 50, "text": "In Datos para un studio geologico de la isla de Luzon (1878), R. von Drasche described soil samples from Porac as “spongy, brilliant white trachyte pumice,” and noticed that the pumice clasts increased in size towards the Zambales mountains,2 but didn’t connect them with Pinatubo."}, {"page": 50, "text": "Oebbeke found pumice in soil he took from Magalang in 1881,3 and probably 42"}, {"page": 51, "text": "Pinatubo in Colonial Times ArAyAt, 1696 The earliest reference to Mount Arayat was made by Italian adventurer-traveler Giovanni Francesco Gemelli Careri (1651- 1725), one of the first Europeans to tour the world using public transportation."}, {"page": 51, "text": "Careri visited Egypt, Turkey, the Holy Land, Armenia, Persia, India, and China, where Jesuit missionaries suspected him as a papal spy."}, {"page": 51, "text": "After seeing the Great Wall, he wrote, “What I thought most ridiculous was to see the wall run up to the top of a vast high and steep mountain, where the birds would hardly build much less the Tartar horses climb.”1 From China he went to Macau and then proceeded to Manila, where he stayed for two months while waiting for a galleon trip to Mexico."}, {"page": 51, "text": "During that time, he wrote in his diary: “In Pampanga, and right on the mountain called Bondo (Bondoc) or Kalaya (Alaya), being a league and a half high (which was previously under the rule of Sinoquoan and Mingan) are plantains, betels and other fruits."}, {"page": 51, "text": "They say they may eat these fruits on the spot, but if anyone carries them down they either fall down dead, or become lame."}, {"page": 51, "text": "Perhaps the devil (by God’s permission) causes such strange accidents, to keep those people in paganism; but the Indians themselves also play their part for they are famous sorcerers and are said often to convert themselves into crocodiles, wild boars and other forms.”2 1 Wikipedia 2Paul Kekai Manansala, Quests of the Dragon and Bird Clan (October 10, 2009) (sambali.blogspot.com). 43 ortsaC xelA"}, {"page": 52, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard wondered where it had come from since it was not consistent with soil from nearby Mount Arayat."}, {"page": 52, "text": "In 1909, an American geologist climbed up and studied Mount Pinatubo itself."}, {"page": 52, "text": "Smith of the US Division of Mines later wrote in the Philippine Journal of Science that “Mount Pinatubo is not a volcano and we saw no signs of it ever having been one, although the rock constituting it is porphyritic (i.e., magmatic).”4 Smith concluded, “The region is quite unique and I have seen nothing in the Philippines quite like it.”5 1 Miguel de Loarca, Relacion de las Yslas Filipinas (1582), in Blair and Robertson’s The Philippine Islands Vol."}, {"page": 53, "text": "SECRET GARdENS Fern canyons, secret gardens, exotic flora and fauna at Mount Pinatubo circa 1900 In the early 1900s, the U.S."}, {"page": 53, "text": "Cavalry transferred their military camp from Talimundok in Angeles town to Sapangbato in the town’s outskirts where there was abundant grass for their horses."}, {"page": 53, "text": "That was the beginning of Fort Stotsenburg, which later expanded to include an airfield called Clark Field."}, {"page": 53, "text": "The Americans stationed there explored the slopes of Mount Pinatubo to search for water sources as well as shortcuts to the sea on the other side of the mountain range."}, {"page": 53, "text": "Myers of the U.S. 26th Cavalry to write a report on possible destinations for trekkers, picnickers and adventure seekers."}, {"page": 53, "text": "In a memo dated January 17, 1925, he described some of the breathtaking scenery he found around Mount Pinatubo: 45 ortsaC xelA"}, {"page": 54, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard First was Fern Canyon, “the finest scenery of its kind around Camp Stotsenburg.” He found it after “From Camp Six crossing two small streams from the Veterinary you should ride Hospital and the Hill Barrio and following a about a mile farther riverbed (most likely the Sacobia). “Here one to the north and can see a beautiful array of typical shrubbery, view Pinatubo Crater. particularly ferns."}, {"page": 54, "text": "Wild fowl abound, especially It’s beyond the smaller birds, many of which are bedecked with description with its the brightest of plumage."}, {"page": 54, "text": "After entering the canyon walls rising it narrows down into a gorge only a few feet wide shear from 500 with walls of solid rock on either side varying from to 2000 feet.” 75 to more than 150 feet in height."}, {"page": 54, "text": "Myers U.S. 26th Cavalry, 1925 out from the walls many feet overhead."}, {"page": 54, "text": "Only at midday does the sun ever reach the depths of the canyon and the air is always cool and laden with the fragrance of wild flowers.” Capt."}, {"page": 54, "text": "Myers also found “interesting and unusual geological formations, including “circular clearings similar to, and which probably are, very old craters.” Called the Three Crater Trail, it led to a stream that furnished the camp’s water supply."}, {"page": 54, "text": "In fact the water line and settling basin were located along this stream (Sacobia), 46 ortsaC xelA American trekkers from Fort Stotsenburg (Clark Field) built tents and posed in front of prehistoric pyroclastic-flow deposits on the slopes of Pinatubo in the early 1900s."}, {"page": 55, "text": "Pinatubo in Colonial Times which led to the Bamban River farther downstream in this area."}, {"page": 55, "text": "The Lost Canyon, so called because it was often overlooked by equestrians, was “a fine place to cool off on hot tropical days.” Everything, Capt."}, {"page": 55, "text": "Myers wrote, was in its natural state. “Varicolored birds flit among the trees and greenery, unconscious of intruders."}, {"page": 55, "text": "Many varieties of epiphytic orchids can be seen as they grow in their natural state.” Across the Bamban River flowed the Second River (Sapang Cuayan) and the Third River (Marimla River) which was “a large pool of cool clear sparkling water."}, {"page": 55, "text": "This is an excellent place for swimming and in years gone by it was quite the thing to arrange swimming parties here.” The Dry River Bed Trail (probably the Mabalacat River or Sapang Balen) ran through a channel east of Hacienda Dolores (Picnic Ground today) where “trees line the stream bed forming natural barriers on either side.” Near this spot was the Banyan Trail where a giant banyan tree stood."}, {"page": 55, "text": "And then there was the Artillery Trail to the China Sea, an ancient path that Americans used to transport their weaponry across the Zambales Mountain Range to the other side."}, {"page": 55, "text": "Soldiers taking this trail passed through Camp Three on the Sacobia River where a good swimming hole was located, and, beyond the four craters, some “marvelous rock formation, reminders of the Pre-Glacial Age” 47 ortsaC xelA “Incomparable with anything in the Philippine Islands."}, {"page": 55, "text": "Its beauty and wonders cannot be appreciated unless seen,” wrote Capt."}, {"page": 56, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard (obviously referring to lahar deposits from the prehistoric eruptions of Pinatubo)."}, {"page": 56, "text": "They then went through a tropical forest that extended to the base of Mount Pinatubo. “The beauty and wonders of this forest cannot be appreciated unless seen,” he wrote, describing the variety A cAmP nAmed sAnchez Formerly known as Camp Four, Camp Sanchez used to be the starting point for ascents to the Pinatubo summit conducted by the 1st U.S."}, {"page": 56, "text": "Cavalry from Fort Stotsenburg in the early 1900s."}, {"page": 56, "text": "In those early days, American soldiers and their families went horseback riding on weekends using old artillery trails."}, {"page": 56, "text": "Those who made it to the top signed a guest book and received certificates as “conquistadores”1 Photo Courtesy: Guy Hilbero and were inducted into the “Ancient and Aromatic Order of the Balugas of Pinatubo” with the rank of caballero.2 The camp was later renamed Camp Sanchez in honor of a Filipino officer in the U.S."}, {"page": 56, "text": "Cavalry who built several stone cottages there."}, {"page": 56, "text": "During World War II, when the Japanese occupied Clark Field, Americans used Camp Sanchez as an observation post to spy on Japanese planes taking off en route to Corregidor and Bataan."}, {"page": 56, "text": "In 1988, when the Philippine National Oil Company (PNOC) started geothermal explorations on Mount Pinatubo, its supervisors used the old stone cottages at Camp Sanchez as living quarters. 1 Alex Castro, viewsfromthepampang.blogspot.com/2008 2 Interview with Guy ‘Indra’ Hilbero. 48 oreblIH yuG"}, {"page": 57, "text": "Pinatubo in Colonial Times From Mount Pinatubo (upper right), American trekkers could see the Capones Island (lower left) on South China Sea. of plants and trees “250 feet tall and 25 to 30 feet in diameter” and “other beautiful flora peculiar to this forest only and never named.” From Camp Three, soldiers proceeded to Camp Four, “a good halfway camp if going to Pinatubo,” which was the headwaters of the Sacobia River and the steep ascent to the mountain began."}, {"page": 57, "text": "The trail then “reaches the divide between the Bamban (Sacobia) and Dry Pasig Valleys (headwaters of the Pasig-Potrero River)."}, {"page": 57, "text": "Four miles later they reached the Zambales Pass and Camp Six (alt. 4000 ft). “The cool climate and invigorating atmosphere rivals Baguio,” Capt."}, {"page": 57, "text": "Myers wrote. “It is an excellent place to camp with plenty of good spring water available.” 49"}, {"page": 58, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard PinAtubo during world wAr ii Mount Pinatubo became a haven for rebels, escapees, deserters and spies during World War II."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Claude Thorpe to establish an observation post overlooking the Japanese-occupied Clark Field."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Thorpe’s unit monitored daily departure time of enemy planes from Clark en route to Bataan and Corregidor."}, {"page": 58, "text": "When Bataan fell in April, Thorpe organized a guerilla unit based in Pinatubo, composed of American and Filipino men who had escaped capture by the Japanese, including Col."}, {"page": 58, "text": "A few Kapampangan women also joined the unit, such as Herminia ‘Minang’ Dizon who served as Thorpe’s personal secretary."}, {"page": 58, "text": "They stayed in the stone cottages that the US Cavalry had built on Camp Sanchez."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Pamintuan had earlier deserted his Huk unit because he realized that the Huk movement had split into those who fought the Japanese and those who fought to install communism."}, {"page": 58, "text": "He said he would rather serve the United States than Japan or the Soviet Union."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Pamintuan recruited three more Kapampangan guerilla leaders, Tomas Lumanlan, Francisco Ocampo and Eugenio Soliman, who brought arms and supplies to Camp Sanchez."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Huk leaders like Luis Taruc and Casto Alejandrino visited the camp."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Pamintuan served as Thorpe’s adviser and confidant while his sons became couriers and bodyguards."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Eventually more and more residents of Angeles volunteered to serve the guerilla unit at Camp Sanchez."}, {"page": 58, "text": "They were divided into three squads: the first to carry supplies from the town to the bottom of the trail, the second to pick them up and relay to Camp Sanchez on Mount Pinatubo, and the third to descend to the bottom of the trail to replace the second squad and repeat the process."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Thorpe was eventually captured and executed by the Japanese."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Source: Behind Japanese Lines: An American Guerrilla in the Philippines by Ray C."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Hunt and Bernard Norling, University of Kentucky Press (1986) 50"}, {"page": 59, "text": "Pinatubo in Colonial Times He then described the view from the Zambales Pass as “incomparable with anything in the Philippine Islands.” To the east were the “plains of Pampanga visible for scores of miles” and to the west “the mountains of the coast and over them the China Sea and the Capones Islands.” “From Camp Six you should ride about a mile further to the north and view Pinatubo Crater."}, {"page": 59, "text": "It is beyond description with its walls rising shear from 500 to 2000 feet,” wrote Capt."}, {"page": 59, "text": "The Americans also discovered a trail to Pasig-Potrero by way of the Sapangbato Ridge, southwest through cultivated farms, a hacienda and a coconut grove."}, {"page": 59, "text": "The dry Pasig bed “is quite wide and persons will have no difficulty in distinguishing it when it is reached.” However, they “will hardly care to ride beyond.” If they did, they’d end up in Bacolor town."}, {"page": 59, "text": "On another side of Pinatubo was the Griffiths Peak, where a small rest house stood at the summit. “On clear days,” wrote Capt."}, {"page": 59, "text": "Myers, “the Central Luzon Valley stretches out to the east and is plainly visible as far as the mountain ranges that run north and south along the Pacific Coast of Luzon (Sierra Madre, Caraballo)."}, {"page": 59, "text": "Angeles, San Fernando, San Pedro Magalang and in fact all of the towns and barrios to the east and south can be seen on clear days.” Capt."}, {"page": 59, "text": "Myers also described a long tunnel which was “large enough for a person to walk through” and “where the water line runs under a high hill.” He also described other hills: the Top o’ the World where the view is “excellent;” a hill called Heaven between the Top o’ the World and Griffiths Peak; the Knife Edge, “very narrow with steep precipitous slopes on either side.” 51 ortsaC xelA On a clear day, American trekkers on Pinatubo could see Magalang and San Fernando"}, {"page": 60, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard mt."}, {"page": 60, "text": "PinAtubo on mount mAnunggAl Some people still think that President Ramon Magsaysay died in a plane crash on Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Actually it was on Mount Manunggal in Cebu."}, {"page": 60, "text": "The crash happened after midnight on March 17, 1957, following a series of speaking engagements at a USAFFE veterans convention and several Cebu universities."}, {"page": 60, "text": "He was with 24 other passengers composed of high-ranking government and military officials as well as journalists."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Only one survived: reporter Nestor Mata of the Philippine Herald."}, {"page": 60, "text": "The confusion over the site of the accident arose because the plane bore the name of another mountain, Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Magsaysay, a native of Iba, Zambales who spoke Kapampangan (a grandparent was from Betis),1 had named the presidential plane after the mountain of his memories."}, {"page": 60, "text": "The day before, he told journalists who were with him on the same plane to Cebu that Pinatubo was “where we hid and fought during my guerilla days.”2 Magsaysay, an automobile mechanic and shop superintendent before World War II, joined the motorpool of the 31st Infantry Division of the Philippine Army when the war broke out."}, {"page": 60, "text": "After the Fall of Bataan, he escaped to Mount Pinatubo and organized the Western Luzon Guerilla Forces."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Pinatubo, a twin-engine C-47, had been newly purchased with less than 100 hours of logged flight."}, {"page": 60, "text": "President Magsaysay had its air-conditioning system removed in response to criticism, which was why he had to apologize to the journalists on board “that we all had to sweat it out.”3 The plane’s five-man crew, all officers of the Philippine Air Force, was led by the pilot, Maj."}, {"page": 60, "text": "It took off from Lahug Airport at 1 A.M."}, {"page": 60, "text": "The President was sitting in his special cabin, right behind the cockpit."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Seventeen minutes later, the plane radioed Malacañang Palace with instructions to have President Magsaysay fetched at Nichols Field at 3:15 A.M."}, {"page": 60, "text": "However, by breakfast time, the plane had gone missing."}, {"page": 60, "text": "The announcement of the President’s death came later in the afternoon."}, {"page": 60, "text": "At the time of his death, President Magsaysay was expected to easily win re-election in the presidential elections in November that year."}, {"page": 60, "text": "He was succeeded by his Vice President, Carlos Garcia. 1Ramon Magsaysay’s Message in Qng Tula Ra Ding Capampangan, the souvenir program for the coronation of Virgen de los Remedios in 1956. 2 Ambeth R."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Ocampo, Looking Back 3: Death by Garrote (Pasig City: Anvil Publishing, Inc.), pp. 27-28. 3 Ibid., p. 28. 52"}, {"page": 63, "text": "Pinatubo Area 1982-1990 Shock Waves The magnitude-7.8 earthquake that destroyed hotels in Baguio City set off shock waves that most likely activated the local faults around Mt."}, {"page": 65, "text": "INCIdENT 1982 - 1990 They were still drilling the mountain the year before the eruption In the mid-1970s, the Marcos government hired the international engineering and construction firm Ebasco Services, Inc. to make a geological evaluation of the Bataan Peninsula-Pinatubo area in connection with the proposed Bataan Nuclear Power Plant (BNPP)."}, {"page": 65, "text": "Through radiocarbon dating, the firm’s geologists were able to identify three previous eruptions of Pinatubo: 635 years ago, 2,330 years ago, and 8,050 years ago.1 Carbon-dating being an inexact science at that time, the dates only roughly coincide with the dates that the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (PHIVOLCS) would later establish."}, {"page": 65, "text": "We do not know if this data was available to the Philippine National Oil Company-Energy Development Corporation (PNOC-EDC) when it started hydrothermal exploration on Mount Pinatubo in 1982, near 5577 sudoxE dna noitpurE"}, {"page": 66, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard an old sulphur mine (a PNOC-commissioned scientific study by F.G."}, {"page": 66, "text": "Pinatubo was well known for its hot springs (some located as far as Porac, Sapangbato and Patling) and occasional steaming (which probably led to the early speculations about its volcanic nature)."}, {"page": 66, "text": "Hydrothermal energy is created when hot vapors from magma rise through cracks in the overlying rocks, heating the rocks and the underground water, which in turn creates steam and hot springs."}, {"page": 66, "text": "Engineers inject water through pipes right into the hot rock layers to create, reopen or widen fractures."}, {"page": 66, "text": "More water is then injected to circulate through the fractured rocks."}, {"page": 66, "text": "Later, additional pipes are drilled to extract the steam energy."}, {"page": 66, "text": "If the government could tap this energy source, it could build a hydrothermal electric plant on Mount Pinatubo which would help solve the country’s energy problem (the 1973 world oil crisis had worsened it). 58 sudoxE dna noitpurE Contractors carved these roads on the slopes of Mount Pinatubo in preparation for the PNOC hydrothermal explorations"}, {"page": 67, "text": "Roused from Dormancy After initial exploration, PNOC-EDC did find a hydrothermal system below Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 67, "text": "As it turned out, that system was being heated by a magma chamber directly under the volcano’s northwestern slope (facing Zambales). (PHIVOLCS would later identify it as the same magma chamber that supplied both the c.1491 and 1991 eruptions.) With technical and consultancy assistance from the Kingston Reynolds Thom and Allardice (KRTA) and the New Zealand Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, PNOC-EDC “Pinatubo has long been asleep, then surveyed Mount Pinatubo until 1986, when the PNOC came and ouster of President Marcos halted the project. drilled around it."}, {"page": 67, "text": "But they had accumulated enough proof that Now it is awakened Pinatubo had sufficient hydrothermal energy, and angry.” and enough reason to convince Marcos’ successor, Victorio Villa, Aeta leader Cory Aquino, to order the project’s resumption. in Zambales 5599 sudoxE dna noitpurE PNOC roads and trails created ugly scars and incisions around Mount Pinatubo (above and upper right photos); steam burst out of one of the drilling pipes, which eventually corroded duM dna eriF duM dna eriF"}, {"page": 68, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard In 1988, PNOC- EDC returned to Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 68, "text": "Workers built a 30-kilometer access road and facilities in three separate drilling sites."}, {"page": 68, "text": "At least three exploratory wells were drilled: the deepest well on the southeastern slope (facing Pampanga) with a vertical depth of 2,733 meters, another on the northeastern slope (2,216 m deep), and a third farther away on the northwestern flank (2,190 m deep)."}, {"page": 68, "text": "As expected, the Aetas living on the slopes of Mount Pinatubo were outraged."}, {"page": 68, "text": "They organized protests and offered animal sacrifices to appease Apu Namalyari."}, {"page": 68, "text": "But the company gave them jobs in the drilling sites and conducted medical and dental missions in the The drilling wells villages, and the drillings proceeded without a reached only a hitch. maximum depth Or so the PNOC-EDC thought. of 2.7 km."}, {"page": 68, "text": "The pipes encountered magmatic fluids Pinatubo’s magma in the hydrothermal reservoir, which initially chamber was still delighted PNOC-EDC officials because the fluids 6 km away. contained more heat than the rest of the system."}, {"page": 68, "text": "However, magmatic fluids have high acidity and high gas content (carbon dioxide, hydrogen sulfide, sulphur dioxide, hydrogen chloride), unlike the neutral-pH chloride waters which are the preferred liquids for hydrothermal energy 60 irallaM leoJ The PNOC pipes did not quite reach Pinatubo’s magma chamber, although when the volcano started steaming in April 1991, one vent coincidentally burst out in the vicinity of a drilling site."}, {"page": 69, "text": "The layers beneath Pinatubo were also found to have limited permeability, which made for poor liquid production."}, {"page": 69, "text": "And so in March 1990, after reaching the conclusion that Pinatubo was not viable for commercial hydrothermal energy, PNOC-EDC cemented the drilling holes and abandoned the project.2 The June 1991 eruptions were only 15 months away."}, {"page": 69, "text": "In July, 1990—barely four months after PNOC-EDC decided to pack up—a magnitude 7.8 earthquake struck Central Luzon."}, {"page": 69, "text": "People are still asking today if the PNOC-EDC hydrothermal exploration at Pinatubo caused, or contributed to, the 1991 eruption."}, {"page": 69, "text": "Although the drilling pipes encountered magma gases, they reached only a maximum depth of 2.7 kilometers."}, {"page": 69, "text": "The magma chamber was at least 6 kilometers below Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 69, "text": "According to PHIVOLCS, Pinatubo’s hydrothermal system was stable in all the years of the PNOC-EDC project; it destabilized only on April 2, 1991, when magma from the magma chamber suddenly intruded the rock layers above it, setting off a chain of events that led to the 1991 eruption two months later.3 Actually, April 2, 1991 was the date PHIVOLCS installed seismic monitoring devices on Pinatubo."}, {"page": 69, "text": "There was really no way PHIVOLCS could have known about the stability or instability of Pinatubo’s hydrothermal system during the PNOC- EDC drillings, because they had no instruments installed there at the time."}, {"page": 69, "text": "Still, the highly acidic fluids with high chlorine content, which corroded the drilling pipes, were already an indication of magma intrusion in Pinatubo’s hydrothermal system."}, {"page": 69, "text": "Magma intrusion was in itself a sign that the hydrothermal system was already unstable even before PNOC-EDC drilled the mountain."}, {"page": 69, "text": "The volcano was probably ripe for an eruption anyway."}, {"page": 69, "text": "PNOC- EDC may have only worsened an already very bad situation."}, {"page": 69, "text": "And the earthquake of 1990 merely quickened the inevitable. 1 Fire and Mud, p. 211. 2 In hindsight, volcanologists wish that PNOC-EDC should not have cemented the drilling wells because the holes would have given scientists the unprecedented opportunity to peep into the temperature, pressure and chemistry of a hydrothermal system on the threshold of a volcanic eruption. 3 Fire and Mud, ibid. 61"}, {"page": 70, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard losing PArAdise Guy ‘Indra’ Hilbero Eyewitness says drillings desecrated the volcano and angered Apo Namalyari Right from the start I had an inkling that Mount Pinatubo would erupt."}, {"page": 70, "text": "I lived in its forests and valleys for long stretches of time, mingling with the Baluga tribes whom I love dearly, and conversing with the spirit of the mountain which I respect and revere."}, {"page": 70, "text": "It is from my Baluga friends that I learned the origin of the name Pinatubo: katutubong nakapinang, or tribesmen in G-string, which describes the people living on its slopes."}, {"page": 70, "text": "It is also from them that I learned about Apo Pinatubo, the God of Power, Lightning and Thunder, who resides in the sacred mountain."}, {"page": 70, "text": "In all those months that I lived in the mountain, I helped my Baluga friends in every way I could."}, {"page": 70, "text": "My friends from the lowlands regularly trekked to Pinatubo to visit me and to bring food and provisions, which I shared with the natives."}, {"page": 70, "text": "I also worked as volunteer for the Military Civic Actions group from Clark Air Base which conducted regular medical and dental missions among the different mountain 62 orebliH yuG 1988 photo shows Pinatubo’s old crater with Hilbero and companion in the foreground."}, {"page": 70, "text": "In his first hike from Sapangbato to San Marcelino via Camp Sanchez, which took three days, Hilbero said he meditated and communed with Nature."}, {"page": 71, "text": "Anderson as executive officer and Ana Gatoc as medical program manager."}, {"page": 71, "text": "Mount Pinatubo meant the world to these tribes, literally and figuratively."}, {"page": 71, "text": "It was their place of worship and the fountainhead of all the things that nourish them."}, {"page": 71, "text": "It is in Mount Pinatubo that all the major river channels in Central Luzon originate."}, {"page": 71, "text": "There’s Marella River that flows through San Marcelino and Maraunot River through Botolan, both in Zambales; O’Donnell River in Capas and Sacobia River in Bamban, both in Tarlac Province; Abacan River in Angeles City, Pasig Potrero River in Bacolor, North Gumain River in Porac, and Porac-Gumain River in Floridablanca, all of them in Pampanga."}, {"page": 71, "text": "Not to mention the countless creeks, streams and springs hydrating the forests and irrigating the farmlands across the region."}, {"page": 71, "text": "Pinatubo was beautiful and pristine, a perfect place to live in for a people as gentle as the Balugas."}, {"page": 71, "text": "This paradise was however shattered in 1988 when a convoy of dump trucks, crane trucks, payloaders and trailers roared their way up to Pinatubo to probe its depths for geothermal energy."}, {"page": 71, "text": "That was the time when the Cory Aquino government was desperately looking for alternative sources of energy following the rise in world oil prices."}, {"page": 71, "text": "The Philippine National Oil Company (PNOC), acting on speculation that Pinatubo was rich with geothermal energy, drilled wells to tap into trapped steam inside the mountain. 63 orebliH yuG Hilbero lived with the Baluga tribes on Mount Pinatubo and Mount Negron for nearly two years (1988-89), which was the time PNOC was drilling the mountain."}, {"page": 71, "text": "He conducted tribal research and documentation on the people he had come to love."}, {"page": 72, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard We watched helplessly as they opened a path from Sapangbato to Inararo, a sitio in Porac, where they set up a base camp."}, {"page": 72, "text": "From this base camp they cleared a thick forest all the way up to Mount Pinatubo, where they marked the first drilling spot (Site A) at 5000 feet above sea level."}, {"page": 72, "text": "For every tree they cut they had to pay the corresponding fee to DENR, or plant a new seedling, as if that would compensate for the environmental calamity they were causing."}, {"page": 72, "text": "Half a kilometer from Site A was a second drilling spot (Site B), which was inclined about 15 degrees on Pinatubo’s slope."}, {"page": 72, "text": "Six to eight kilometers farther north, 64 orebliH yuG In April 1994, Hilbero returned to Pinatubo “where freedom and adventure take flight,” he wrote."}, {"page": 72, "text": "Here shown with Aetas and friends with the post-eruption summit."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Roused from Dormancy in the vicinity of a Baluga village called Patal Pinto in the Crow Valley bombing and gunnery range, was Site C."}, {"page": 73, "text": "The PNOC sourced the water used as coolant in the drilling operations from Camp Sanchez, an old encampment (built in the 1920s) on a plateau about 3.9 kilometers from the summit of Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Formerly known as Camp Four, Camp Sanchez is the navel of Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 73, "text": "The water flowing through Marella River towards San Marcelino, Zambales originates in this camp."}, {"page": 73, "text": "It was named after a Filipino US Army Cavalry officer who first explored the site in the 1920s."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Pinatubo was only one of the places in the country that PNOC was exploring at the time."}, {"page": 73, "text": "They also drilled on Mount Natib in Bataan, where local insurgents burned their heavy equipment and threw them into deep ravine."}, {"page": 73, "text": "There was Mount Apo in Davao, where Haribon Philippines helped locals mount protest actions."}, {"page": 73, "text": "There was also a drilling site in Cagayan Valley which was where PNOC later transferred their equipment after the Pinatubo site closed."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Right from the start, the Balugas led by their apo (chieftain) had opposed the PNOC project at Pinatubo."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Aside from the desecration of their holy mountain, the tribal leaders were appalled by the scandalous behavior of PNOC personnel who brought gambling, cigarettes, liquor and prostitutes to the camp."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Even the Baluga men and boys who worked for the project were corrupted."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Sabangan, the Regional Director of the Office of Northern Cultural Communities (ONCC), saw these things himself."}, {"page": 73, "text": "The accidental death of the Baluga chieftain’s child was, to me, the first warning sign of Pinatubo’s wrath."}, {"page": 73, "text": "The child and his playmate had taken a dip in a pool of tailing water containing high levels of sulfur and acid from the Site A drilling."}, {"page": 73, "text": "The PNOC settled the case by paying for the children’s funeral and hiring the chieftain, Apo Jungle, as member of the seven-man Forest Rangers unit of the Philippine Army, headed by a Sgt."}, {"page": 73, "text": "This accident was followed by the simultaneous deaths of six more children in the Aeta settlement of Mabulilat under Apo Logan."}, {"page": 73, "text": "PNOC did not even bother to investigate this."}, {"page": 73, "text": "The villagers told me they suspected sulfur and acid contamination of the river which was the source of their drinking water."}, {"page": 73, "text": "And then there was this freak storm that leveled trees around Pinatubo and caused landslides."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Strong winds blew away almost all the thatched houses at Camp Sanchez, Lumboy, Mabayabas and Mt."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Abo, including the new multi-purpose buildings that had been built by a Korean Presbyterian missionary, Pastor Philip Lee and Sister Ruth."}, {"page": 73, "text": "They were there to do community work with the Aetas, including providing board and lodging for stay-in Aeta schoolchildren from the surrounding villages."}, {"page": 73, "text": "After the storm, the Presbyterian mission had to start from scratch again."}, {"page": 73, "text": "Lastly, PNOC itself suffered heavy losses when their heavy equipment fell into deep ravines due to landslides."}, {"page": 73, "text": "In December 1989, after spending two years and over 200 million pesos, PNOC started dismantling their huge drilling machines."}, {"page": 74, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard acidic—that is, the drilling pipes melted before reaching the mountain’s thermal nerve."}, {"page": 74, "text": "They cemented the holes at site B, site A and site C in that order."}, {"page": 74, "text": "An insider told me, though, that the real reason was they had run out of budget, but that they would return in 1993 on a fresh loan from the World Bank."}, {"page": 74, "text": "He added that they had, in fact, lined up 18 new drilling sites starting in Brgy."}, {"page": 74, "text": "When Mount Pinatubo finally erupted on June 12, 1991, followed by the paroxysmal eruptions on June14, 15 and 16, the magma came out of the old crater and, more significantly, out of the PNOC drilling sites."}, {"page": 74, "text": "This volcano had been dormant for 500 years."}, {"page": 74, "text": "Why it awakened in 1991, and not 50 or 100 or another 600 years later, I don’t know."}, {"page": 74, "text": "Probably the 1990 earthquake shook up its plumbing system and loosened some plugs."}, {"page": 74, "text": "Probably the PNOC drillings caused some cracks that allowed magma to seep through."}, {"page": 74, "text": "What I know is Mount Pinatubo rearranged our landscape, altered history and changed millions of lives forever."}, {"page": 74, "text": "The Americans abandoned Clark but I know they only shrugged the experience off with the quip “It’s just another day in Paradise.” For my Baluga friends and family, however, it’s the day they lost their Paradise. 66 orebliH yuG Hilbero and friends at Pinatubo’s peak in April 1994."}, {"page": 74, "text": "In the background is the majestic Mount Arayat; on the left is Mt."}, {"page": 74, "text": "Palanisca (partially hidden) and behind the group are Mt."}, {"page": 74, "text": "The pyroclastic-flow deposits, shown here beside Mt."}, {"page": 74, "text": "Dorst, would bury Cabalantian in the following year."}, {"page": 75, "text": "THE lUzON EARTHqUAkE July 16, 1990 The magnitude 7.8 temblor rattled the local faults around Pinatubo The largest fault in the country, the Philippine Fault, starts in eastern Mindanao, goes northwest through Leyte, Masbate, then off the coast of Quezon province, reenters Luzon through Dingalan, Aurora before splaying in Digdig, Nueva Ecija and radiating into several local faults towards La Union, Mountain Province and Ilocos."}, {"page": 75, "text": "All in all, it’s a 1200 km-long fault running through Luzon, Visayas and Mindanao.1 On Monday, July 16, 1990, at 4:26 P.M—barely a month after PHIVOLCS officials told a conference in Baguio City that they had discovered a sub-fault of the Philippine Fault located below a Nueva Ecija town named Digdig2—a magnitude 7.8 earthquake struck 6677"}, {"page": 76, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Central and Northern Luzon."}, {"page": 76, "text": "The earthquake originated almost exactly where PHIVOLCS said it would: the Digdig section of the Philippine Fault."}, {"page": 76, "text": "Although not the strongest earthquake in Philippine history, it was certainly the most destructive: it killed 1,621 people and left a swath of destruction over an area of about 20,000 square kilometers."}, {"page": 76, "text": "It also produced a 125-km ground rupture that stretched from Dingalan, Aurora to Cuyapo, Nueva Ecija, as well as a new sub-fault that cut across Baguio City."}, {"page": 76, "text": "In Cabanatuan City, “A tectonic which is only a short distance from the quake’s earthquake with epicenter, the collapse of the six-story Christian that big a magnitude College of the Philippines killed 154 students as July 16 can and teachers."}, {"page": 76, "text": "In Dagupan City, liquefaction trigger a volcano caused buildings to sink as much as 1 meter."}, {"page": 76, "text": "In eruption.” La Union, 100,000 families lost their homes due Delfin Garcia, PHIVOLCS to liquefaction in coastal villages.3 In Baguio City, hotels and buildings collapsed, including the Hyatt Terraces and Hotel Nevada, where the wife of a former Central Bank Governor died."}, {"page": 76, "text": "The quake was felt in Manila, the Southern Tagalog Region and even Bicol Region."}, {"page": 76, "text": "In Pampanga and Clark Field, it measured magnitude 6—strong enough to send thousands of students at Holy Angel University and other schools in Angeles City running out of buildings in panic."}, {"page": 76, "text": "Less than two hours later, at 6:10 P.M., a magnitude 4.8 earthquake struck the Mount Pinatubo area, about 10 kilometers southeast 68"}, {"page": 77, "text": "Roused from Dormancy A network of local faults and subfaults radiate from Mount Pinatubo, including the Sacobia Lineament and the Maraunot Fault, both of which became the path of the similarly named river channels. of the crater."}, {"page": 77, "text": "Was it an aftershock from the major earthquake?"}, {"page": 77, "text": "PHIVOLCS describes it as an “aftershock” in quotation marks, meaning it was synchronous with other aftershocks from the distant major quake but did not originate from the Digdig fault that had triggered the major quake."}, {"page": 77, "text": "A recent study by the University of Utah Seismograph Stations shows that major quakes can trigger not only aftershocks but also smaller tremors in distant areas, sometimes as far as another continent."}, {"page": 77, "text": "These tremors are different from aftershocks, which occur close to the major quake."}, {"page": 77, "text": "For example, the 2004 Sumatra earthquake led to quakes in Equador, on the opposite side of the planet.4 The Pinatubo quake on July 16, 1990 was most likely caused by interaction of the major quake’s seismic waves with a local fault that was already stressed by previous magma intrusion.5 In other words, the big Luzon earthquake made the local fault at Pinatubo produce its own local quake."}, {"page": 77, "text": "Like all active volcanoes, Pinatubo has its own network of sub- faults."}, {"page": 77, "text": "One of them is the Sacobia Lineament (so called because satellite image shows it as a straight line on the Sacobia river valley pointing towards Pinatubo) which intersects with the Maraunot Fault exactly where Mount Pinatubo stands."}, {"page": 77, "text": "Another is the Tayawan Fault which intersects with Dangey Fault in the northern flank of Mount Pinatubo.6 6699 duM dna eriF"}, {"page": 78, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard The mountain continued to vibrate with quakes until late July."}, {"page": 78, "text": "On August 4, or 19 days after the earthquake, Sister Emma Fondevilla, a Franciscan nun working with an NGO called Lubos na Alyansa ng mga Katutubong Ayta ng Sambales (LAKAS) in Poonbato, Zambales went to PHIVOLCS to deliver a report from her Aeta friends about a landslide, rumbling sounds, and “black and grey smoke from a fissure” on the northwest slope of the mountain the day before."}, {"page": 78, "text": "Kelvin Rodolfo, a geologist and visiting professor from the University of Illinois in Chicago, and Dr."}, {"page": 78, "text": "Chris Newhall of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) were at the PHIVOLCS office during the nun’s visit.7 The next day, the Philippine Daily Inquirer carried a story headlined “Zambales folk flee as mount ‘acts up’” while the People’s Journal PAst And future doomsdAy scenArio The Maraunot Fault, a sub-fault of the Iba Fault, is a fracture on the northwestern flank of Mount Pinatubo which can be traced by following the direction of the Maraunot River and the location of several hot springs (buried since the 1991 eruption)."}, {"page": 78, "text": "The Maraunot river valley is the site of massive landslides and erosions from lake breakouts on the caldera summit of ancestral Pinatubo, which wiped out everything in their path as the rampaging water and volcanic debris fanned out across Zambales."}, {"page": 78, "text": "The same scenario was building up after the 1991 eruption when a lake started forming on the caldera."}, {"page": 78, "text": "The water was rising dangerously close to a gap in the caldera rim which was right where the active Maraunot Fault is located and where the steep Maraunot river valley starts."}, {"page": 78, "text": "If that gap was breached, water from the 2.5 km caldera plus 6 cubic kilometers of volcanic debris on the slopes would cascade towards Botolan and neighboring towns."}, {"page": 78, "text": "Fortunately, heavy rains in July 2002 scoured the gap and partially released water from the caldera lake, thus minimizing the pressure and averting another catastrophic lake breakout… for the time being."}, {"page": 78, "text": "The crater lake still lies atop the mountain almost one kilometer above sea level; the Maraunot Fault is still active and can cause the crater rim to collapse; landslides can block the widened gap once again and cause sudden water rise inside the caldera; and the magma dome beneath the lake can still grow with succeeding minor eruptions and can push out large volumes of lake water."}, {"page": 78, "text": "Lagmay, “Geology and hazard implications of the Maraunot Notch in the Pinatubo caldera, Philippines” in Bulletin of Volcanology, Vol. 69, No. 7 (June 2007), pp. 797-809. 70"}, {"page": 79, "text": "Roused from Dormancy quoted PHIVOLCS Director Dr."}, {"page": 79, "text": "Raymundo “Preliminary findings Punongbayan as saying that if the smoke was indicate that the white, there was no danger, but if it was black, phenomenon is not the people should evacuate."}, {"page": 79, "text": "They were the related with any first-ever articles on the Pinatubo saga."}, {"page": 79, "text": "Dr. volcanic activity.” Punongbayan sent a PHIVOLCS team the same PHIVOLCS memo dated August 6, 1990 after helicopter day to inspect the mountain from a helicopter. survey of mount pinatubo The team later allayed fears of volcanic activity, dismissing the smoke as dust and ash thrown up by the landslide."}, {"page": 79, "text": "The next day, the Manila Chronicle reported that the smoke at Pinatubo was white, while the Manila Times said it was black."}, {"page": 79, "text": "Two days later, the Philippine Star carried a story headlined “Govt. bodies conflict on Mt."}, {"page": 79, "text": "Pinatubo,” referring to the Philippine National Police (PNP) which reported that the July 16 earthquake created a huge crater at Pinatubo, the Office of Civil Defense (OCD) which denied the crater story and downplayed the event, the 7711 duM dna eriF Aetas saw black and grey smoke from the western and northwestern flanks of Pinatubo shortly after the July 16, 1990 earthquake."}, {"page": 79, "text": "The Maraunot River valley, which is a local fault, is in the lower middle, while a PNOC camp is in the lower right."}, {"page": 80, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Zambales Provincial Council which announced that the experts had found sulfur on the cracks at Pinatubo, and PHIVOLCS which found no signs whatsoever that the dormant volcano would erupt.8 Dr."}, {"page": 80, "text": "Rodolfo, who reviewed the PHIVOLCS team’s videotape showing “heavy continuous steaming,” later said he was puzzled by PHIVOLCS’ interpretation."}, {"page": 80, "text": "Geology, he said, is never done properly from aerial photos; a hike up the mountain would have revealed more and hazard evaluation might have started much sooner."}, {"page": 80, "text": "But, he added, PHIVOLCS, like other government agencies, was chronically under-funded and was too focused at the time on Taal Volcano to make a thorough ground assessment on Pinatubo.9 After those days of anxiety over Pinatubo, nothing more was heard from PHIVOLCS or from anyone else."}, {"page": 80, "text": "The nation’s (and the world’s) attention had turned to Saddam Hussein’s invasion of Kuwait, which would later lead to the Gulf War."}, {"page": 80, "text": "Beneath the mountain, however, something akin to war was also brewing. 1 Bartolome C."}, {"page": 80, "text": "Bautista et al. “The 16 July 1990 earthquake and its Aftershocks Activity” in The July 16 Earthquake: A Technical Monograph. 2 Raymundo S."}, {"page": 80, "text": "Punongbayan “The 16 July 1990 Luzon Earthquake Ground Rupture” in The July 16 Earthquake: A Technical Monograph. 3 Wikipedia 4 Kris Pankow et al., Nature Geoscience, online journal (May 25, 2008). 5 Fire and Mud, p. 354 6 Ibid., p. 351. 7 Kelvin S."}, {"page": 80, "text": "Rodolfo, Pinatubo and the Politics of Lahar (Quezon City: UP Press), p. 76. 8 Ibid., p. 308. 9 Ibid., p. 76. 72"}, {"page": 82, "text": "10 - 15 million years ago Born of the Sea Pinatubo was conceived at the bottom of the ocean and carried to full term in the bosom of the planet."}, {"page": 82, "text": "Eons ago, when the floor of South China Sea slid down into the Earth’s mantle below Luzon island, the subduction resulted in magma mixing which created the arc of volcanoes that include Pinatubo."}, {"page": 85, "text": "WHERE GOd HAS PUT US The Philippines is located in the worst possible spot on the planet— the Ring of Fire and the Typhoon Belt It’s one of those geologic processes that we need some stretching of the imagination to understand: The Earth we live in was once a ball of molten rock and metals; the metals, which were heavier, sank to become the Earth’s core, while the rest of the molten rock gradually cooled and solidified and became the Earth’s mantle."}, {"page": 85, "text": "The process is not as neat as it sounds; the molten parts kept melting the parts that had already solidified, and the solid parts kept fracturing, releasing gases that eventually became the Earth’s atmosphere, as well as steam that eventually condensed to become the Earth’s oceans."}, {"page": 85, "text": "Today, molten rock continues to percolate inside the mantle because the heat coming from the core creates convection currents similar to what a turbo broiler does."}, {"page": 85, "text": "The heated material rises and seeks an opening in the overlying crust; the opening is usually a fracture located at the thin section of the crust (ocean floor)."}, {"page": 86, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Molten rock seeps out through fractures (ridge) on the thinnest section of the earth’s crust (ocean floor)."}, {"page": 86, "text": "The seepage pushes the crust apart and causes it to fold up (mountain range) or slide under (subduction). and becomes new crust."}, {"page": 86, "text": "The seepage pushes the fractured ocean floor in opposite directions, and since the Earth is round, the pushed sections of the crust will eventually collide somewhere."}, {"page": 86, "text": "When they do, they either crumple up (forming mountain ranges) or slide down (causing a phenomenon called subduction)."}, {"page": 86, "text": "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge, a long gash on the floor of the Atlantic Ocean, is the spot where such seepage occurs."}, {"page": 86, "text": "It is the reason South America and Africa, once attached to each other, continue to drift apart about two to eight centimeters a year—more or less the rate a fingernail grows.1 If you look at a world map, you can see that continents and islands can actually fit together like pieces of a jigsaw puzzle."}, {"page": 86, "text": "This jigsaw puzzle more or less reflects a mosaic of fissures on the crust."}, {"page": 86, "text": "The fissures are the dividing lines between plates—the term used for the slabs of rock floating on a viscous mantle, like ice cubes floating on water."}, {"page": 86, "text": "Unfortunately for us, the Philippines is located between two subduction zones, in a fragment of a plate wedged between two much larger plates: the Eurasian Plate which is moving from west to east, and the Philippine Sea Plate, which is moving from east to west."}, {"page": 86, "text": "These two plates act like a clamp that’s compressing our micro-plate and causing it to further crack up into fragments."}, {"page": 86, "text": "Today numerous regional faults crisscross the entire length of the badly deformed archipelago. 78"}, {"page": 87, "text": "Hell Below Us The fractured continental plates look like pieces of a jigsaw puzzle that once fitted perfectly into each other until they floated apart."}, {"page": 87, "text": "The Philippines is sandwiched between two plates that are moving--not apart but towards each other!"}, {"page": 87, "text": "As the Eurasian Plate and the Philippine Sea Plate continue to push towards each other, you would think that only one of them would give in."}, {"page": 87, "text": "Instead, both plates are going under—the Eurasian Plate subducting off the coast of Zambales, and the Philippine Sea Plate subducting off the coast of Aurora."}, {"page": 87, "text": "On the map they look like two long gashes on the sea floor: the Manila Trench in South China Sea and the Philippine Trench in the Philippine Sea."}, {"page": 87, "text": "Due to discrepancies in subduction, the pressure from the Eurasian Plate is causing central Luzon to rotate counterclockwise, while the pressure from the Philippine Sea Plate is causing the Philippine Sea basin to rotate clockwise—two tectonic wheels spinning in opposite directions!2 As if the place was still not volatile enough, in the midst of the colliding, sliding, and spinning plates sprouted the most dangerous volcano in the archipelago."}, {"page": 87, "text": "The story of Mount Pinatubo began deep in South China Sea, in the ugly scar on the sea floor called the Manila Trench."}, {"page": 87, "text": "The sea floor is normally 1.5 kilometers deep, but in the trench where the constantly moving Eurasian Plate subducts, it plunges 4 kilometers deeper."}, {"page": 87, "text": "As the plate creeps, bends and descends into the abyss, it brings down with it materials from the seabed—water, sand, marine debris—to about 100 kilometers into the brittle portion of the 79"}, {"page": 88, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard earth’s mantle."}, {"page": 88, "text": "There, high pressure and high temperature alter the very chemistry of the rocks and, in a process that’s really hard to understand, produce copious quantities of water that rise and melt rocks into magma."}, {"page": 88, "text": "And because magma is less dense than the surrounding rocks, it also rises through the fissures in the overlying mantle rocks."}, {"page": 88, "text": "When magma cannot find a path upwards, it pools into a magma chamber where it stays for a while until more magma pushes it from below."}, {"page": 88, "text": "It continues rising and seeping through cracks until it finally reaches the surface, where it breaks out and piles up debris which forms into a mountain."}, {"page": 88, "text": "That’s how volcanoes are born. worst PlAce to build A nucleAr PlAnt The discovery of the crisscrossing faults between the two major subduction systems sandwiching Luzon island is one of the reasons the Bataan Nuclear Power Plant (BNPP) project was scrapped."}, {"page": 88, "text": "One local fault has been located in southern Pampanga."}, {"page": 88, "text": "It appears on satellite image as a sharp linear depression in Lubao town pointing directly towards Mount Natib, at the foothills of which stands the nuclear plant."}, {"page": 88, "text": "Called the Lubao Lineament, the fault line is connected to Mount Natib, which is actually a volcano with a history of Plinian (explosive) eruptions."}, {"page": 88, "text": "In fact, although not obvious from the ground, Mount Natib has a huge caldera for a crater."}, {"page": 88, "text": "Scientists also say that Napot Point, the exact spot where the nuclear plant has been built, is an old pyroclastic- flow deposit from a massive prehistoric eruption, about 27,000 years ago."}, {"page": 88, "text": "As a rule of thumb, the longer a volcano stays in repose, the more time it has to store energy, and therefore the larger the eventual eruption will be."}, {"page": 89, "text": "Hell Below Us Philippine Trenches and Faultlines The Philippines is wedged between two subduction zones, the east-moving Manila Trench and the west-moving Philippine Trench, which act like a clamp that is compressing, fracturing and fragmenting the archipelago into many faults."}, {"page": 89, "text": "Aside from the major Philippine Fault, there are regional faults like the Marikina Fault and local faults like those around Mount Pinatubo. 81"}, {"page": 90, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Mount Pinatubo is only one of many volcanoes in a chain that marks the line of magma ascent in Luzon.3 Actually, there are two chains: the volcanic alignment in the Zambales Mountain Range that includes Mount Pinatubo, Mount Mariveles, Mount Natib, Mount Negron and Mount Kuadrado, and a parallel arc that includes Mount Arayat in Pampanga and Mount Bangcay, Mount Amorong and Mount Balungao, all in Pangasinan.4 When there are too many volcanoes in one area, it can only spell trouble: they are like lesions on the earth’s skin that hint of an underlying fever condition."}, {"page": 90, "text": "They may be quiet now but just because a volcano does not erupt in a hundred or even thousand years does not mean it is a dead volcano. “Extinct volcano” is an oxymoron.5 Volcanoes are either active or asleep (dormant); a sudden jerk or slip in the subducting plate can cause sudden magma rise that can make even a dead volcano come back to life. 1Jelle de Boer et al. “The Bataan Orogene: Eastward subduction, tectonic rotations, and volcanism in western Pacific (Philippines),” Tectonophysics Volume 67, Issues 3-4, 20 August 1980, Pages 251-282 2Ibid. 3Defant, M."}, {"page": 90, "text": "Voyage of Discovery: From the Big Bang to the Ice Age."}, {"page": 90, "text": "Mancorp. pp. 325. 4 Jean-Christophe Gaillard, “Arayat’s Ancient Upheavals” in Singsing Magazine Vol. 1 No. 3 (Holy Angel University), p.10. 5Kelvin S."}, {"page": 90, "text": "Rodolfo, Testimony given on behalf of the Philippine Climate Watch Alliance to the House Committee on Appropriations on February 2, 2009. 82"}, {"page": 91, "text": "Hell Below Us volcAnology 101 Kapampangans would be told later that they barely escaped being toasted alive by the planet’s most horrific scourge: pyroclastic flows Pinatubo’s eruption in 1991 turned most Kapampangans into volcanology experts or, to be more precise, enthusiasts."}, {"page": 91, "text": "Their constant and intimate exposure to the nuances of volcanic activity taught them, for example, the difference between lava and pyroclastic flow, between pyroclastic flow and lahar flow, between viscous lahars and dilute lahars, etc."}, {"page": 91, "text": "Unlike Bicolanos and Batangueños who grew up in the shadow of their respective volcanoes, there was nothing in their history that prepared Kapampangans, intellectually or psychologically, for a volcanic eruption."}, {"page": 91, "text": "And so when Pinatubo acted up, they crammed on geology, volcanology and seismology to understand the forces of nature 83 )PA( nadroJ divaD moc.ytipid Slow-moving lava, which Pinatubo does not produce."}, {"page": 91, "text": "Before June 15, Kapampangans thought this was the kind of volcanic debris they would be dealing with."}, {"page": 91, "text": "Instead, Pinatubo produced pyroclastic flows, which were worse than lava."}, {"page": 91, "text": "Pyroclastic flows appear like billowing clouds... ...which glow like hot charcoal at night."}, {"page": 92, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Indonesians were killed on the spot when a 2010 eruption of Mount Merapi produced pyroclastic flows that blew across nearby villages."}, {"page": 92, "text": "Kapampangans could have suffered the same fate had Pinatubo’s pyroclastic flows reached Pampanga on June 15 that were suddenly turning their world upside down."}, {"page": 92, "text": "Some new words added to their vocabulary: tephra, the general term for ash, pumice sand, rock fragments and any material blasted out during a volcanic eruption, carried upward by a convecting column of hot gases, and fall back to the earth as ash fall, pumice rain, rock missiles, etc.; pyroclasts or pyroclastic debris, the specific term for liquid magma that solidify as rock fragments upon contact with air; pyroclastic flows, dense cloudlike mixtures of hot gases and pyroclastic debris that flow down a volcano’s Pyroclastic flows killed Camiguin residents slopes like an avalanche; caused by after a 1951 Mt."}, {"page": 92, "text": "Hibok-Hibok eruption fountaining or collapsing eruption column; each flow can move as fast as 300 kph and can reach distances of up to 150 km; if you are overrun by a pyroclastic flow, your first breath will kill you by searing your lungs."}, {"page": 92, "text": "Merapi in Indonesia were all burned 84 moc.retsambewnaiiawaH"}, {"page": 93, "text": "Hell Below Us and buried by pyroclastic flows."}, {"page": 93, "text": "Had Pinatubo’s 1991 eruption been a litle stronger and lasted a little longer, such deadly flows would have overtopped Pinatubo’s foothills and river channels and swamped communities in Pampanga, Tarlac and Zambales, including Clark Air Base. pyroclastic-flow deposit, the flow when it runs out of momentum after reaching a distance; the deposit continues to smolder until water (from rain or river) causes it to explode and produce billowing ash clouds Pyroclastic flows, not lava, from Mt."}, {"page": 93, "text": "Vesuvius in called secondary explosions; A.D. 79 buried these Pompeii citizens lava dome, a mound-like protrusion on the crater produced by viscous (slow moving) lava lava, glowing stream of nonviscous (runny) magma coming out of the crater; Pinatubo is the type of volcano that does not produce lava, only pyroclastic flows; caldera, a crater at least 1 km in diameter; formed when the summit is destroyed during an explosive eruption or when the crater floor collapses into the magma chamber beneath the volcano; lahars (always plural), pyroclastic-flow deposits remobilized by water; they behave like mudflows but are hotter and have the consistency, viscosity and density of concrete; lahar deposit, lahars When citizens in nearby Herculaneum ran to the that spread out on a plain and seashore to evacuate, Mt."}, {"page": 93, "text": "Vesuvius’ pyroclastic harden; much of Pampanga and flows overran and killed them, too."}, {"page": 93, "text": "Tarlac stand on prehistoric lahar deposits. 85"}, {"page": 95, "text": "CHAMbER OF HORRORS A main magma chamber lies only 6 kilometers below Pinatubo Pinatubo’s magma chamber is only 6 kilometers below the mountain—that’s half the distance between the poblacions of Angeles City and the City of San Fernando."}, {"page": 95, "text": "It was formed millions of years ago when rising molten rock from the earth’s mantle seeped through rock fractures until it encountered a rock layer that it could not break, so it collected in a pool—a reservoir where the ebb and flow of magma determined whether the volcano above it would erupt or stay dormant."}, {"page": 95, "text": "Actually, magma chamber is a misnomer because it is not really a cavernous pocket that needs to be filled with semi-liquid magma."}, {"page": 95, "text": "Magma chambers are also hard rock, except that they are more porous than the surrounding rock."}, {"page": 95, "text": "It is the rock’s porous character that allows the magma to flow through. 87"}, {"page": 96, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Some magma chambers are shallower than others."}, {"page": 96, "text": "In the case of Mount Pinatubo, not only is its magma chamber shallow—it has at least three magma chambers beneath it, corresponding to the other volcanoes in its vicinity."}, {"page": 96, "text": "The main magma chamber holds 40 to 90 cubic kilometers of magma; it is located below the ridge connecting Mount Pinatubo and Mount Negron."}, {"page": 96, "text": "Attached to it is another magma chamber below the adjacent Mount Negron."}, {"page": 96, "text": "A third magma chamber is located below the northwest slope of Pinatubo, directly under the caldera that formed in 1991."}, {"page": 96, "text": "It is this third magma chamber that supplied the 1991 eruption."}, {"page": 96, "text": "The total capacity of this cluster of magma chambers under Mount Pinatubo is 125 cubic kilometers."}, {"page": 96, "text": "The total amount of magma ejected by Pinatubo in 1991 was 5 cubic kilometers, which means only a small percentage of the magma inside the chamber was expelled.1 There are cases where one magma chamber supplies fuel for two adjacent volcanoes, which means they can erupt simultaneously, as what happened in Papua New Guinea in 1937 when two volcanoes, 6 kilometers apart, erupted at the same time."}, {"page": 96, "text": "Thus, Mount Negron and Mount Pinatubo can erupt simultaneously in the future, in which case the eruptions can be so massive that the loss of volume in the magma chamber can cause the ridge between the two mountains to collapse and form a large caldera.2 88 ude.nogerou.segap Mt."}, {"page": 96, "text": "Pinatubo had a network of magma chambers similar to that of another volcano pictured above One magma chamber lies beneath Pinatubo, another beneath Mt."}, {"page": 96, "text": "Negron (shown in upper right) and a third beneath the ridge between Pinatubo and Mt."}, {"page": 97, "text": "Hell Below Us Sequence shows new magma intruded Pinatubo’s magma chamber on or before April 2, mixed with the old magma inside before rising to the chamber’s ceiling and fracturing the old conduits leading to eruptions on June 12-15 After the last eruption of the Buag Eruptive Period, Pinatubo’s magma chamber cooled down by filling with felsic magma, the type that doesn’t cause eruptions because it is composed of dacite rocks with very high silica content—an extremely viscous (dense and heavy) and inert magma."}, {"page": 97, "text": "It was this magma that plugged the crater and pushed the dome that eventually gave the mountain its pre-1991 conical shape."}, {"page": 97, "text": "Dormant volcanoes normally take hundreds to thousands of years before erupting again because that’s the time needed for the magma in the chamber to reheat and become unstable again.3 Although the intervals between Pinatubo eruptions were progressively narrowing, the 500-year gap between the Buag Eruptive Period and the 1991 eruption was the shortest ever—quite short, actually, by Pinatubo standards (the gap between Buag and the one before it was 1,600 years; the previous others were even longer)."}, {"page": 97, "text": "The magma chamber beneath Pinatubo did not take the usual centuries-long, even millennia-long, reheating process because a different type of magma intruded the chamber and destabilized it."}, {"page": 97, "text": "Sometime in late 1990 or early 1991, mafic magma—composed 89"}, {"page": 98, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard of basalt which is nonviscous (runny)— penetrated the base of the chamber and started accumulating there."}, {"page": 98, "text": "The Luzon earthquake, strong enough to cause fractures in rock layers, could have been the culprit."}, {"page": 98, "text": "The quakes felt on the night of July 16, 1991 (barely two hours after the Luzon earthquake) were the ominous sign."}, {"page": 98, "text": "Once inside the magma chamber, the superheated mafic magma (1,250°C) melted the viscous felsic magma (780°C) at the base of the reservoir."}, {"page": 98, "text": "The melted (molten), liquidized felsic magma could now mix with the nonviscous, syrupy mafic magma, in the process also creating a new magma called andesite (intermediate between mafic and felsic)."}, {"page": 98, "text": "Scientists have a specific date for this event: April 2, 1991."}, {"page": 98, "text": "It was the day Pinatubo started venting steam into the atmosphere."}, {"page": 98, "text": "But that was also just the day PHIVOLCS installed earthquake monitoring devices on the volcano’s slopes, so it is possible that unrecorded smaller earthquakes, signifying magma intrusion and mixing, had occurred earlier than April 2."}, {"page": 98, "text": "The freshly molten magma, now less dense, started to rise through the chamber, forcing the rest of the chamber contents to mix."}, {"page": 98, "text": "As it rose to the chamber’s ceiling, the mixing slowed down a bit after the rising magma encountered semi- rigid dacite rocks overlain by solid dacite rocks."}, {"page": 98, "text": "Despite the obstacles, the mixing process inside Previously, Pinatubo the chamber was quite rapid, occurring in just needed 500 years to bake before two weeks (May 20 to June 3, 1991). exploding."}, {"page": 98, "text": "In 1991, The mafic-led mixed magma then searched the intruding magma for the old conduits to the surface, fracturing took only months to rock layers to clear its path."}, {"page": 98, "text": "Meanwhile, the fill the chamber and denser felsic magma could not rise as fast until reach the surface a wider passage was created. 90"}, {"page": 99, "text": "Hell Below Us The first eruption on June 12, 1991 was accompanied by little or no pumice fall because the magma that first came out contained very little dacite (felsic) magma."}, {"page": 99, "text": "However, that eruption widened the vent or, to use a volcanologist’s description, cleared its throat."}, {"page": 99, "text": "This vent-widening process continued through June 13 and 14 as Pinatubo kept erupting."}, {"page": 99, "text": "On June 15, the conduit was now wide enough for large quantities of dacite magma to extrude, and Pinatubo exploded with a dacite-filled Plinian eruption."}, {"page": 99, "text": "Pinatubo’s slow waxing phase ended with a more rapid waning activity."}, {"page": 99, "text": "The decompressed magma chamber led to its collapse, starting with the roof."}, {"page": 99, "text": "The collapse reestablished the original pressure conditions preventing further magma rise and thereby resealing the magma chamber.4 Scientist Alain Burgisser of the Universites d’Orleans et de Tours in France studied Pinatubo’s magma temperatures, the size of its magma chamber, the crystal concentration inferred from study of its magmas, etc. and made a mathematical model showing that 20 to 80 days were sufficient to activate the magma chamber, as compared to the conventional theory that Pinatubo’s magmas needed 500 years to bake before exploding.5 Considering that only two months elapsed between the April 2 incident and the June 12 eruption, Burgisser’s calculations appeared accurate. 1Fire and Mud, pp. 380-381. 2Ibid., p. 381. 3Burgisser, Alain, Orleans Institute of Earth Sciences, CNRS/Universites d’Orleans et de Tours, “Magma Chambers Awake Sooner Than Thought” (The Watchers website, March 6, 2011-04-17). 4 Scandone, Roberto, Dipartimento di Fisica, University di Roma Tre, “Factors Controlling the Evolution of Large Explosive Eruptions” JVGR). 5Burgisser, ibid. 91"}, {"page": 102, "text": "sr. emma Fondevilla reports explosions, PHiVolcs sets up steam emissions monitoring station at usGs sets up to PHiVolcs sitio yamut, Botolan observatory at clark APril 2, 1991 mAy 20 mAGmA PenetrAtes mAFic & Felsic FresHly molten BAse oF cHAmBer mAGmAs miX mAGmA rises to (possibly caused by insiDe cHAmBer, cHAmBer ceilinG 1990 local earthquake) ProDuce neW mAGmA, in neXt 2 WeeKs AnDesite (until June 3)"}, {"page": 103, "text": "April 2, 1991 - June 11, 1991 Giant Awakens The white steam clouds the day after April Fools only aroused mild curiosity among scientists and military officials at Clark."}, {"page": 103, "text": "It was a Franciscan nun living with the Aetas who rang the alarm bells."}, {"page": 103, "text": "PHiVolcs raises Dailies announce Alert level 5 “Pinatubo erupts!” “eruption in clark personnel progress” evacuate to subic mAy 20 June 6-12 June 9 June 10 June 12 June 13-14 FresHly molten mAGmA seArcHes olD PinAtuBo “cleArs PinAtuBo mAGmA rises to conDuits, FrActures tHroAt,” WiDens Vent continues cHAmBer ceilinG rocK lAyers to AlloW lArGer to WiDen Vent in neXt 2 WeeKs quAntities oF mAGmA (until June 3) to escAPe"}, {"page": 105, "text": "OMINOUS SIGNS August 1990 - April 1991 An erupting volcano was the last thing the stressed-out Americans at Clark wanted to hear From August, 1990 to April, 1991, as the nation came to terms with the earthquake’s tragic consequences and the aftershocks slowly faded away, a strange calm surrounded Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 105, "text": "Grass had started to grow over the landslide area on the northwest slope, and Aetas had returned to their hunting routine, occasionally encountering trekkers from the lowlands in search of bonsai trees, orchids and adventure."}, {"page": 105, "text": "Six kilometers below the mountain, however, was another story."}, {"page": 105, "text": "The continuous seepage of magma through cracks at the bottom of the magma chamber had heated up the old magma contents in the reservoir."}, {"page": 105, "text": "The relatively rapid development was inconsistent with the usual timetable of Pinatubo’s eruptive history."}, {"page": 105, "text": "But by April Fools Day the magma had opened the floodgates at the bottom of the 97 moc.rotatcepsnoitaiva"}, {"page": 106, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard chamber and was now mixing in earnest with the old magma inside."}, {"page": 106, "text": "The depressurized gases pushed the overlying old magma deposits in the vents and came in contact with the same hydrothermal system that the PNOC-EDC had tried to tap."}, {"page": 106, "text": "The explosion blew the plugs off the vents and sent white steam into the air."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Aetas in Sitio Tarao and Sitio Yamut on the Zambales side heard the explosions on April 2, 1991, while Clark residents on the Pampanga side noticed the steam rising out of Pinatubo in the same morning."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Sister Emma Fondevilla of Poonbato—the same nun who had reported the landslide and rumbling sound to PHIVOLCS in August, 1990—waited two days before reporting the incident to PHIVOLCS."}, {"page": 106, "text": "On April 5, Director Raymundo Punongbayan dispatched a Quick Response Team to conduct an aerial survey."}, {"page": 106, "text": "From the helicopter, the volcanologists saw an alignment of nine vents vigorously emitting white steam."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Their initial assessment was that the steam came from the preexisting hydrothermal system."}, {"page": 106, "text": "To further monitor the situation, PHIVOLCS set up the first monitoring station at Sitio Yamut in Brgy."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Villar in Botolan, Zambales, about 7 km from Pinatubo."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Julio Sabit OIC, PHIVOLCS Volcano Monitoring and Eruption Prediction Division PHIVOLCS formed a quick response team (QRT) composed of Arturo Daag, Gerry Diolata and myself."}, {"page": 106, "text": "On April 5, upon our arrival at Yamut, a sitio of Brgy."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Villar about 7 km from the summit, Sister Emma offered a nipa hut as our temporary field monitoring station and quarters."}, {"page": 106, "text": "We installed a portable seismograph at 4 P.M."}, {"page": 106, "text": "During our first night, at least four earthquakes were felt accompanied by rumbling sounds."}, {"page": 106, "text": "By 6 A.M. of April 6, the seismograph had detected more than 400 high-frequency volcanic earthquakes."}, {"page": 106, "text": "We processed the data but were not able to transmit it to the main office because our team was not able to bring any communications equipment."}, {"page": 106, "text": "We were lucky because OCD Region III Director Armando Duque came via helicopter that same morning and we requested him to bring our report to PHIVOLCS, Quezon City."}, {"page": 106, "text": "Punongbayan instructed us to send our observation report via the military radio network in Iba, Zambales."}, {"page": 106, "text": "A military vehicle fetched us for this purpose."}, {"page": 106, "text": "After three days, PHIVOLCS sent us a single-side band radio which allowed us to regularly provide bulletins and messages to the main office. 98"}, {"page": 107, "text": "Magma Rising Americans at Clark saw this white plume on April 2 and wondered what it was."}, {"page": 107, "text": "At the Crow Valley bombing range in Capas, U.S. servicemen noticed the O’Donnell River turning muddy and emitting sulfuric stench."}, {"page": 107, "text": "According to Guy Hilbero, the servicemen noticed rocks rolling down from the PNOC Site C in Patal Pinto. “When I went to check,” Hilbero said, “I saw columns of steam rising from vents, as well as carcasses of cattle lying around and dead fish and talunasan (freshwater eel) floating in ponds near Durungawan.” At Clark Air Base, the Americans who went on their morning jog around the parade ground saw the white plume but thought nothing of it."}, {"page": 107, "text": "However, in the routine staff meeting of Clark military officials held later that day, someone mentioned the curious smoke in passing."}, {"page": 107, "text": "One official who had already done some research told the group that the smoke came from a mountain called Pinatubo and that Pinatubo was in fact a volcano, although a dormant one."}, {"page": 107, "text": "What volcano?”1 A volcano was the last thing the stressed-out Americans wanted to hear that day."}, {"page": 107, "text": "Negotiations between the United States and the Philippines over lease extension for Clark and the Subic Bay Naval Station had just taken a turn for the worse."}, {"page": 107, "text": "The lease was scheduled to expire in September, 1991 and the U.S. wanted to extend it."}, {"page": 107, "text": "Manila was seeking $825 million a year for only a seven-year extension, while 99"}, {"page": 108, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Washington was willing to pay only $360 million a year for a 10- to 12-year extension. (In reality, the two parties were only $30 million apart, because only half of the amount demanded by the Philippines was in cash and the rest were in trade concessions and debt relief.) Although most Americans living at Clark and Subic considered the bases worth the price Filipinos were asking for, the U.S."}, {"page": 108, "text": "Joint Chiefs of Staff, Congress and the White House remained unconvinced."}, {"page": 108, "text": "The bases’ strategic value was expected to decline with the impending end of the Cold War (the Soviet Union would collapse in December, 1991), which meant less budget for defense."}, {"page": 108, "text": "President Cory Aquino was also perceived as unable or unwilling to rein in the anti-U.S. elements in her administration."}, {"page": 108, "text": "And then there was the assassination of two servicemen in May, 1990 (apparently by the New People’s Army), which prompted Clark officials to order a ‘lock down,’ i.e., those who lived on base could not leave the base, and those who lived off-base could only use designated routes to and from work."}, {"page": 108, "text": "Eventually, Clark personnel assumed a siege mentality.2 Clark Air Base, occupying 10,000 acres of land only 14 kilometers from Mount Pinatubo, was the largest United States Air Force (USAF) base outside the continental United States."}, {"page": 108, "text": "It served as the primary refueling and service stop for the C-130 and C-5A aircraft that transported supplies to U.S. forces in the Indian Ocean and Western Pacific."}, {"page": 108, "text": "Over 15,000 servicemen lived in Clark, with 4000 more military retirees and their families staying in subdivisions in adjacent Angeles City and Mabalacat."}, {"page": 108, "text": "Subic, about 56 kilometers away from the volcano, provided the U.S."}, {"page": 108, "text": "Seventh Fleet with an extensive network of petroleum storage sites, supply depots and repair bases.3 Approximately 10,000 Filipinos worked at Clark, many of them as maids, yard boys, cooks and caddies."}, {"page": 108, "text": "About 3000 of them who worked as clerks, secretaries, librarians and accountants were in the direct payroll of the United States government.4 Over the years, Clark personnel developed close personal and business ties with the locals living outside."}, {"page": 108, "text": "In fact, the robust economy of the adjacent towns—quite progressive compared to the rest of the province—was due largely to their hundred-years-old relationship with the military base."}, {"page": 108, "text": "To the residents of Angeles City and Mabalacat, whether they worked on base, sold PX goods, rented out apartments, watched FEN- 100"}, {"page": 109, "text": "Magma Rising TV, or took Americans as boyfriends or baptism sponsors, the thought that Clark Air Base might close or the Americans might leave was simply unbearable."}, {"page": 109, "text": "The Americans on base were equally anxious."}, {"page": 109, "text": "Aside from the NPA assassinations and the lock down, the 1990 earthquake forced many servicemen to participate in relief and rescue operations in Baguio and Cabanatuan."}, {"page": 109, "text": "This was followed by a walkout of 3000 Filipino employees at Clark whose labor union had voted to strike."}, {"page": 109, "text": "The ten-day strike led to another lock down because some of the strikers had threatened servicemen with violence.5 As if these Striking labor union members were not enough, there were the coup attempts outside the gate of Clark Air Base against Cory Aquino, one of which prompted the United States to send U.S. jets from Clark to Pinatubo was not show support for her beleaguered government. “the kind where you sit on your front Soon Clark personnel were sporting T-shirts porch, sip a cocktail, with the words “I survived…” followed by a and wonder if it will list of mishaps in the Philippines: typhoons, get to your property assassinations, floods, strikes, coup attempts, within the next four earthquakes.6 generations.” And so when told that a volcano had just Rick Hoblitt, USGS been discovered just a short distance from their during a briefing to Clark officials in April largest offshore military base and that it might soon erupt, Clark officials could express only disbelief and exasperation."}, {"page": 109, "text": "On the west side, PHIVOLCS asked government agencies to order precautionary evacuation of about 4000 Aetas living within 10 kilometers of the summit."}, {"page": 109, "text": "They were herded into hastily organized evacuation camps."}, {"page": 109, "text": "According to Guy Hilbero, the evacuees from Patal Pinto, Mag-ube, Bangan Tungol, Alunan, Durungawan, Duray, Kubol and Tambo were assigned to the Santa Juliana Elementary School in Patling, Capas, while those from Villar, Palis, 101"}, {"page": 110, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Naculcul and Magisgis were transferred to Poon Bato on the west side."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Villagers from Inararo and Camachiles were moved to the Angeles City Trade School and those from San Martin, Santa Rosa, Burog and Sto."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Niño were relocated to safer grounds in Bamban."}, {"page": 110, "text": "President Aquino visited the evacuation site at Santa Juliana, gave a short speech, and left."}, {"page": 110, "text": "The portable seismographs that PHIVOLCS set up in Yamut had been busy recording more than 100 quakes a day."}, {"page": 110, "text": "The quakes originated only 5 kilometers below the surface—an indication that magma was nearing the surface."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Strangely, Taal Volcano in Batangas also began to experience swarms of earthquakes."}, {"page": 110, "text": "It divided PHIVOLCS’ attention and drew the public attention away from Pinatubo to the more dangerous volcano in the south."}, {"page": 110, "text": "But Pinatubo was finally recognized as a serious Julio Sabit PHIVOLCS Life at sitio Yamut was very difficult and depressing."}, {"page": 110, "text": "The village was located in a remote area planted with root crops, corn, bananas and a few fruit trees."}, {"page": 110, "text": "There were no vegetables to supplement our dietary needs."}, {"page": 110, "text": "The team did not bring cooking implements, plates, cups and spoons because the investigation was initially scheduled for only a couple of days."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Fortunately, Sister Emma and Sister Minggay lent us cooking implements and occasionally vegetables and fruits."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Otherwise, we survived each day on canned goods and dried fish because we had no vehicle and Yamut is 20 km away from Botolan town proper."}, {"page": 110, "text": "The nearest sari-sari store was in Burgos, about 6 km to the south."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Sometimes we ate camote and whatever local fruits we found."}, {"page": 110, "text": "We paid the Aetas to fetch water for us because the source of potable water was 1.5 km downhill."}, {"page": 110, "text": "The nearby Maraunot River was heavily silted so we took a bath at the Murasa River, about 5 km from Yamut."}, {"page": 110, "text": "Botolan Mayor Tito Doble sometimes provided us something to eat as well as gasoline. 102 )retfA sraeY 005 :obutaniP .tM( gnamgaD nuJ President Cory Aquino visited the first evacuees after Pinatubo became restive"}, {"page": 111, "text": "Magma Rising The seismographs and other monitoring devices that PHIVOLCS had set up on the slopes of Mt."}, {"page": 111, "text": "Pinatubo in April promptly recorded as many as 100 quakes a day threat on April 10 when sulfurous fumes killed one person and sent many others to the hospital."}, {"page": 111, "text": "On April 16, the Manila Times carried the headline “Pinatubo nears point of eruption.” By that time, Pinatubo was experiencing more tremors The USGS-PHIVOLCS observatory on Maryland Avenue near Clark’s parade ground than Taal."}, {"page": 111, "text": "Chris Newhall of the USGS, who was based in Seattle, Washington with his Bicolana wife."}, {"page": 111, "text": "Newhall and team arrived at Clark on April 24."}, {"page": 111, "text": "Clark officials gave them a two-story, four-unit base house on Maryland Avenue, which was on the southwest side of the parade ground."}, {"page": 111, "text": "It had a view of Mount Pinatubo from the second-floor windows."}, {"page": 111, "text": "They named the house Pinatubo Volcano Observatory (PVO)."}, {"page": 111, "text": "Meanwhile, the PHIVOLCS team initially planned to set up office in a school or an apartment in Angeles City."}, {"page": 111, "text": "When base officials invited them to join the USGS at Clark, Dr."}, {"page": 111, "text": "Punongbayan worried that with the contentious bases talks still ongoing in Manila, staying at Clark would compromise PHIVOLCS’ neutrality, put the Filipino 103"}, {"page": 112, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Abong Tayag Former President, Angeles City Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Inc."}, {"page": 112, "text": "I went to Inararo and found only Americans there with their monitoring equipment."}, {"page": 112, "text": "They recorded earthquakes so they knew magma was rising."}, {"page": 112, "text": "Murphy discouraged us from going but we went anyway."}, {"page": 112, "text": "The Americans definitely knew Pinatubo would erupt."}, {"page": 112, "text": "After spending the night there, we returned to Pampanga and immediately mobilized people."}, {"page": 112, "text": "We presented an evacuation plan to Governor Guiao."}, {"page": 112, "text": "In the plan, it would take 10 hours to evacuate Pampanga, because the only available exit was San Fernando. scientists in an awkward situation, and lessen the frequency and credibility of their bulletins to other Philippine agencies and units."}, {"page": 112, "text": "However, the advantages of access to helicopters, scientific equipment, communication facilities and other logistical support available at Clark outweighed the political disadvantages, and so the PHIVOLCS team moved to Clark on April 26.7 Like the USGS scientists, the Filipino volcanologists were issued ID cards and gate passes. “The USGS volcanologists were all PhD degree holders, while their counterparts at PHIVOLCS were all just young employees,” Dr."}, {"page": 112, "text": "Leonila ‘Leyo’ Bautista, an Associate Scientist “I had no idea how at PHIVOLCS, recalls. “But during meetings to deal with this the Americans treated us like co-equals."}, {"page": 112, "text": "They information on encouraged us to share our ideas, no matter how either a personal or ridiculous they must have sounded to them.”8 professional level."}, {"page": 112, "text": "The joint USGS-PHIVOLCS team installed What they had just seven seismometers (seismographs) in different said scared me, really spots around Pinatubo, and two tilt meters scared me.” near the summit."}, {"page": 112, "text": "The seismometers recorded Richard Anderegg 3rd Tactical Fighter Wing vibrations while the tilt meters measured Vice Commander, Clark Air Base, after USGS warned ground swelling or tilting, which would mean that pyroclastic flows could engulf Clark Air Base that the volcano was bulging and ready to 104"}, {"page": 113, "text": "Magma Rising explode. (A seismogram is the sheet of paper where the needle prints the seismic waves recorded by a corresponding seismometer on the volcano.) The computers at the PVO were programmed to measure the earthquakes’ location and depth, amplitude and frequency—all indicators of the behavior of magma as it rose and fractured rock layers."}, {"page": 113, "text": "High-frequency quakes meant magma was forcing its way through solid rock, while low-frequency quakes suggested magma was getting closer to the surface.9 Ironically, as the U.S. and Philippine bases extension panels (led respectively by Richard Armitage and Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus) locked horns over sticky points of the negotiations, USGS and PHIVOLCS scientists at Clark were actually enjoying their cooperation on Pinatubo."}, {"page": 113, "text": "Although there were suspicions that USGS’ pronouncements about Pinatubo tended to play up the threat and therefore minimize the viability of Clark and favor the Americans 105 duM dna eriF Volcanologists who inspected the site made this sketch of the ash vents around the mountain."}, {"page": 114, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Media men stayed with the PHIVOLCS team at Poonbato and accompanied the scientists in their daily routine of changing the seismograph paper."}, {"page": 114, "text": "It gave them a front-row view of the restive volcano."}, {"page": 114, "text": "Julio Sabit PHIVOLCS Third week of April, we transferred our monitoring station from sitio Yamut to Barangay Burgos due to continued increase in activity."}, {"page": 114, "text": "In May, we began detecting an unusually high number of earthquakes, more than 100 high-frequency events per day."}, {"page": 114, "text": "We transferred our remaining seismograph at Yamut to sitio Ogik and our monitoring station from Burgos to Poonbato, where it was more accessible to media and the public."}, {"page": 114, "text": "It was a small structure but it had toilet and bath."}, {"page": 114, "text": "We also intensified our information campaign by attending more barangay meetings."}, {"page": 114, "text": "Poonbato residents relied not only on what we said but also on what we did to guide them on what to do."}, {"page": 114, "text": "For example, every time we moved away from the volcano, they also did the same."}, {"page": 114, "text": "Some media people stayed with us, even accompanying us in our daily tasks of changing the seismograph paper, conducting visual observation of the volcano, etc."}, {"page": 114, "text": "Even the Governor of Zambales occasionally visited us. 106 )yrutneC eht fo noitpurE ehT :obutaniP( timgaS kciN"}, {"page": 115, "text": "Magma Rising The theatre at Clark scheduled a showing of the old film “Last Days of Pompeii” on June 14."}, {"page": 115, "text": "U.S. servicemen never got to watch it because they evacuated on June 10. in the bases negotiations, or that they provided information to Clark officials but not to—or at least ahead of—Philippine officials, the USGS-PHIVOLCS team vowed to remain apolitical and to follow the agreed-upon procedure of providing bulletins first to the Office of Civil Defense, and then to all other interested parties including the U.S."}, {"page": 115, "text": "Punongbayan also assigned the PHIVOLCS main office in Quezon City as the only source of public issuances so that the Filipino volcanologists at Clark could concentrate on their work."}, {"page": 115, "text": "After a few weeks of monitoring and evaluation, the team concluded that Mount Pinatubo was indeed preparing to erupt and that the eruption was going to be Plinian."}, {"page": 115, "text": "In a briefing with Clark officials, they asked the USGS chief what Plinian meant."}, {"page": 115, "text": "Newhall said it was the type that was going to be messy and explosive like Mount Saint- Helens, with lots of pyroclastic flows."}, {"page": 115, "text": "Anderegg, asked, “What is pyroplastic?” Dr."}, {"page": 115, "text": "Hot fragments that roll down the volcano’s flanks in enormous clouds."}, {"page": 115, "text": "So dense they wipe out everything in their path.” Dr."}, {"page": 115, "text": "Newhall added that pyroclastic flows would go through Sacobia and Abacan rivers like they did 107"}, {"page": 116, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard in previous eruptions."}, {"page": 116, "text": "It was entirely possible, he said, that the flows could jump the banks and inundate Clark Air Base.11 Only 13 kilometers from Mount Pinatubo, Clark’s main housing area could be engulfed in pyroclastic flows within five minutes of the eruption."}, {"page": 116, "text": "Across the table, the military officials sat stunned."}, {"page": 116, "text": "This crisis had no precedent in the 90-year history of Clark Air Base—or in the history of any military base on the planet."}, {"page": 116, "text": "The prospect of Clark turning into Pompeii, and 15,000 military personnel and their families being killed instantly, was beyond comprehension."}, {"page": 116, "text": "There was no other way to respond to the situation: the entire population of the United States’ biggest offshore military base must be evacuated. 1 C.R."}, {"page": 117, "text": "PINATUbO ANd UNClE SAM Most Kapampangans considered the closure of Clark Air Base not only unacceptable but also unthinkable One uncanny coincidence in the Pinatubo story is how the volcano erupted in precisely the year the R.P.-U.S."}, {"page": 117, "text": "Military Bases Agreement was set to expire, thus ending all debate on whether or not the treaty should be extended."}, {"page": 117, "text": "For Filipino nationalists, the timing couldn’t have been better."}, {"page": 117, "text": "For the Americans, it couldn’t have been worse."}, {"page": 117, "text": "The Agreement was forged in 1947 when the United States and the Philippines shook hands to give the U.S. the right to continue using their military bases here for 99 more years (until 2046), after occupying them since 1903."}, {"page": 117, "text": "The two countries needed the Agreement because it would ensure their mutual protection at the time of Cold War (which started in 1947), the Korean War (which started in 1950) and the Vietnam War (which started in 1955). 109 ude.godsciryl"}, {"page": 118, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard What the Americans did not anticipate was the tide of nationalism in the Philippines that kept pressuring them to renegotiate the terms of the Agreement."}, {"page": 118, "text": "In 1966, for example, the expiry date of the Agreement was reset from 2046 to 1991."}, {"page": 118, "text": "In 1979, Clark Air Base came under the control of the Armed Forces of the Philippines (Clark Air Base Command or CABCOM) headed by a Filipino base commander; his American counterpart became a mere senior officer and commander of the U.S."}, {"page": 118, "text": "In 1990—the year before the Agreement’s expiry date— events seemed to conspire to make the Americans feel they weren’t welcome anymore."}, {"page": 118, "text": "In May, the New People’s Army (NPA) killed two U.S. airmen outside Clark, forcing a lockdown on U.S. personnel for several days."}, {"page": 118, "text": "In July, a Magnitude 7.8 earthquake rocked the military facility and the rest of Luzon."}, {"page": 118, "text": "In October, the base workers union voted to strike."}, {"page": 118, "text": "The threat of strike-related violence forced another base lockdown."}, {"page": 118, "text": "And yet the White House sent a team headed by Richard Armitage to renegotiate the Agreement, with instructions to replace it with a new one."}, {"page": 118, "text": "When the AFP took control, for example, a canopy in the shape of a native “salakot” was built right before the gate."}, {"page": 119, "text": "Magma Rising instead that she would “keep my options open.” But relations between the two countries turned for the worse just as the negotiations were starting."}, {"page": 119, "text": "Robert Gates, Deputy National Security Adviser of the first President Bush, privately met with Cory and told her bluntly to “get your house in order.” Cory was reportedly “stunned.” She was further incensed when U.S. officials leaked details of the Gates meeting to U.S. media, as well as when U.S."}, {"page": 119, "text": "Congress cut $96 million off the proposed $481 million assistance package to the Philippines."}, {"page": 119, "text": "Cory struck back by snubbing Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney who was due to arrive in Manila."}, {"page": 119, "text": "Shocked and angered, Washington officials called it boorish behavior and suspected it was nothing but a gambit to extort more aid for the bases."}, {"page": 119, "text": "Toby Roth of Wisconsin, member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, said, “Let them keep their bases."}, {"page": 119, "text": "We do not want them, we do not need them."}, {"page": 119, "text": "They are only an albatross around the necks of the American people.” The avuncular President Bush advised Cory, “Listen, every time I talk to Dick Cheney I come away smarter."}, {"page": 119, "text": "In 1986, when President Marcos was ousted from power, U.S. helicopters took him to Clark where he spent the night at the Chambers Hall (now Holiday Inn Hotel)"}, {"page": 120, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard me, maybe you could learn from the man, or he could learn from you.” Even Cory’s trusted friend, Teddy Benigno, wrote in his column, “We lose a lot in this refusal, because it is based on personal pique and not on the national interest.” By national interest he meant the $1 billion a year in rent and other expenditures that the bases brought to the country."}, {"page": 120, "text": "In January 1991, the United States turned over Wallace Air Station (located in La Union) to the Philippine government as a goodwill “Listen, every time gesture, but the Filipino negotiators led by Raul I talk to Cheney Manglapus were not impressed."}, {"page": 120, "text": "I come away The Philippine panel offered only a seven- smarter,” the first year extension and a guaranteed fixed rental fee President Bush told of $825 million a year."}, {"page": 120, "text": "The U.S. panel pledged President Cory only $360 million a year but even that amount 112 gro.aohw Violence often marred union strikes and anti-bases rallies outside the Clark gate..."}, {"page": 121, "text": "Magma Rising was on the condition that the extension should be “Her personal ten years minimum. pique is costing The collapse of the negotiations seemed the country imminent. $1 billion a year in base rental.” To the people of Angeles City, which hosted Clark Air Base, and of Olongapo City, which Teddy Benigno Columnist and hosted Subic Naval Base, the largest U.S."}, {"page": 121, "text": "Navy Cory’s trusted friend installation in the Pacific, the closure of the bases was something they were not prepared to accept or even to imagine."}, {"page": 121, "text": "The social, economic, and emotional ties between base personnel and the residents in the surrounding communities dated back to the start of the American colonial period in the early 1900s."}, {"page": 121, "text": "But just as temperatures rose to sizzling point in the summer of 1991, a volcano just a short distance west of Clark and east of Subic stirred and settled the matter once and for all. 113 gro.aohw ... which prompted AFP-CABCOM soldiers to come in and restore order for the Americans."}, {"page": 122, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard In May, 1991, scientists gathered baseline data about Pinatubo’s prehistoric eruptions by studying the layers of pyroclastic-flow deposits in the Sacobia and Abacan rivers 114"}, {"page": 123, "text": "MOUNTING PRESSURE May, 1991 With only a few precious days left before the eruption, scientists still couldn’t tell the public anything definite about Pinatubo While Americans at Clark worried over Pinatubo, it was business as usual for Filipinos living outside the base."}, {"page": 123, "text": "Word that a mountain nearby might erupt hardly caused a bump in sales among bars and massage parlors around Clark, and managed to get only a few seconds of airtime in the evening news."}, {"page": 123, "text": "Local government officials assumed the most convenient stance—a state of denial—all through the month of May."}, {"page": 123, "text": "Because Pinatubo was erupting for the first time in recorded history, scientists had no baseline information about the volcano except hastily collected pyroclastic-flow deposits in the Abacan and Sacobia river channels, which gave them an idea—but only an idea—of Pinatubo’s prehistoric eruptions."}, {"page": 123, "text": "It was this lack of data 115 duM dna eriF"}, {"page": 124, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard “Because these that prevented the USGS-PHIVOLCS team from (prehistoric) deposits making early and specific predictions, which led flanked Clark Air to some public confusion and disappointment."}, {"page": 124, "text": "Base, we informed Meanwhile, the monitoring devices at the base officials there Pinatubo Volcano Observatory at Clark showed was a chance (small, a chimney of magma forming vertically below but not zero) that the the volcano, and pointing directly toward the base would be swept fissure on Pinatubo’s northwest slope—the same by pyroclastic flows vents that were producing the steam columns. or hot lahars, either Six kilometers below, there was turbulence of which would be deadly.” inside the magma chamber: the new magma at the base of the reservoir was now rising and mixing Dr."}, {"page": 124, "text": "Raymundo Punongbayan PHIVOLCS Director rapidly with the old magma."}, {"page": 124, "text": "This turbulence, as well as the expansion of the chamber, was caught by the scientists’ equipment as high-frequency (or fast) earthquakes."}, {"page": 124, "text": "On May 13, PHIVOLCS issued a five-level Volcano Warning System which was designed to be simple enough to be understood by local residents but not too simple to exclude the nuances of volcanic activity. (The system’s compromise design eventually became its own undoing when, in the quieter days after the climactic June 15 eruption, PHIVOLCS created new panic among the already panic- weary population by raising the alert level to the maximum 5—“eruption in progress.” PHIVOLCS had used the warning system’s technical definition of an eruption—growth of a dome—to make the decision."}, {"page": 124, "text": "It later amended the definition to include “accompanied by large explosions.”) 1 But, as Dr."}, {"page": 124, "text": "Punongbayan explained, “it was difficult to ponder the most effective style of warnings when we ourselves were still struggling to anticipate the volcano’s activity.” Even with the swarms of earthquakes indicating imminent eruption, he knew that if the rising magma hit 116"}, {"page": 125, "text": "Magma Rising a rock layer that it could not crack, all volcanic activity could cease and Pinatubo could go back to sleep for another hundred years."}, {"page": 125, "text": "And even if magma ascent continued, volcanoes behaved in geologic—not calendar—time, which means that the volcano could be restless for years, decades and centuries before actually erupting.2 In addition to the volcano warning system, PHIVOLCS also issued a Pyroclastic-Flow Hazard Map which showed the extent of expected pyroclastic flows."}, {"page": 125, "text": "The scientists based the map on ancient pyroclastic deposits."}, {"page": 125, "text": "For example, if they found ancient deposits in Sapangbato but not beyond, they put the village within the hazard zone in the belief that the next pyroclastic flow would retrace its path."}, {"page": 125, "text": "To be safe, PHIVOLCS extended the zone to another kilometer just in case the next eruption would be larger than the last one (although Pinatubo’s eruptive pattern indicated it would be smaller)."}, {"page": 125, "text": "Photocopies of the hand-sketched hazard map were distributed to Pampanga government officials during a briefing on May 23."}, {"page": 125, "text": "Copies were also sent to President Aquino and her Cabinet, including then-Defense Secretary and Chairman of the National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) Fidel V."}, {"page": 125, "text": "On May 27, copies were presented to Tarlac officials during their own briefing and would also have been presented to Angeles City officials on the same day had they attended a briefing scheduled specifically for them.3 Their non-appearance Skeptical and even betrayed their apathy, skepticism and outright hostile, Angeles hostility to what they considered irresponsible officials snubbed a speculations about a volcano in their vicinity."}, {"page": 125, "text": "PHIVOLCS briefing Such speculations, they said, could potentially and blasted what they hurt the local economy and throw a monkey called irresponsible wrench on the bases negotiations. speculations 117"}, {"page": 126, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard The hazard map eventually proved inaccurate because it included only the communities along river channels where pyroclastic flows might pass, but not the alluvial plains where lahars might spread out."}, {"page": 126, "text": "PHIVOLCS at the time was focused on the impending eruption and possible pyroclastic flows during, not after, the eruption. (It was only after June 15, when scientists had seen the actual volume of pyroclastic deposits, that they issued a more detailed map, which was no longer called a pyroclastic-flow hazard map, but a Lahar Hazard Map, in anticipation of water-induced remobilization of deposits.) Clark officials took an interest in the PHIVOLCS map, which showed the pyroclastic flows reaching only the periphery of the military base’s housing area."}, {"page": 126, "text": "To them, the map represented a comforting second opinion to the earlier prediction that pyroclastic flows could “(The residents’) engulf all of Clark. usual reaction was PHIVOLCS issued posters and brochures disbelief that any to educate a public that was dealing with a volcano existed volcano for the first time."}, {"page": 126, "text": "The materials gave in their backyard, only general instructions about what to do much less one that during an eruption: wear a dust mask, sweep might erupt. (Local the ash fall off rooftops, and evacuate to higher government officials) ground in case of mudflow (although no one wanted to do the really understood what a mudflow was). right thing for their PHIVOLCS also sent its scientists to local constituents but schools and socio-civic organizations to answer found it difficult to frequently asked questions about volcanoes. even imagine the Everybody wanted to know whether or not ash problem."}, {"page": 126, "text": "Terms like pyroclastic flow, fall was poisonous, and whether or not lava and mudflow, and ash fall rock missiles could reach their communities. were completely new No question was asked, and no information was and meant little to volunteered, on the possibility of the eruption them.” column being so huge it could turn day into Dr."}, {"page": 126, "text": "Punongbayan night, or could dump so much ash and sand on 118"}, {"page": 127, "text": "Magma Rising rooftops that they could actually collapse."}, {"page": 127, "text": "The word “pyroclastic flow” was tossed around quite often in the open forums, but no one had an idea just how real and how big the danger was."}, {"page": 127, "text": "Some people were actually looking forward to witnessing a volcanic live show."}, {"page": 127, "text": "In the end, it was a Betamax tape that proved to be PHIVOLCS’ most effective campaign material."}, {"page": 127, "text": "It contained a video done by the late volcanologist Maurice Kraff which showed shocking footage of lahars, pyroclastic flows, and volcanic landslides, recorded in various eruption sites all over the world."}, {"page": 127, "text": "Copies of the tape circulated and were watched by families at home and shown in schools and parish halls."}, {"page": 127, "text": "Not a few skeptics were converted, realizing for the first time that a volcanic eruption meant more than trickles of glowing lava. 1Fire and Mud, p. 73. 2Anderegg, p. 15. 3Ibid., p. 75. 119 suaL yveL As the slopes of Mt."}, {"page": 127, "text": "Pinatubo continued to smolder, Kapampangans went about their usual business."}, {"page": 127, "text": "It was less than a month before the eruption."}, {"page": 128, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Josie Henson President, Akademyang Kapampangan On June 2, my elder brother Edmin finally convinced me to go on a trek to Mt."}, {"page": 128, "text": "The whole family tagged along--Apple, the youngest daughter of Edmin, my eldest brother Vic, Ben, Raoul, Butch, Jai-Jai, and myself."}, {"page": 128, "text": "Off we drove in his 4-wheel-drive Land Rover."}, {"page": 128, "text": "The trip, through the rugged terrain of Sapangbato and further up the mountains took almost an hour."}, {"page": 128, "text": "As everything was spur-of-the-moment, I forgot to bring my camera."}, {"page": 128, "text": "Fortunately, my brother Edmin brought his."}, {"page": 128, "text": "As soon as we reached the “Staging” area (so-called because this was where the PNOC people drilled Kapampangans called the ancient pyroclastic-flow deposits planas pipes hoping to discover then tap geothermal energy from the bowels of Mt."}, {"page": 128, "text": "We felt the temperature get lower and the cool breeze very refreshing."}, {"page": 128, "text": "Down below was a cascading river and we quickly descended the rather steep slopes, got into our shorts and soaked ourselves in the cool rushing waters with gushing mini-waterfalls here and there."}, {"page": 128, "text": "We marveled at the natural beauty of the lofty hills around us."}, {"page": 128, "text": "These hills were like green pinnacles reminiscent of the emerald hills of Guilin in China, with one difference: in China the verdant hills were of limestone, while the hills near the foot of Mt."}, {"page": 128, "text": "Pinatubo were of hardened sand or planas as it is known in Kapampangan."}, {"page": 128, "text": "When expertly hewn, these hardened planas made good building blocks and our Holy Rosary Parish Church was built in the early eighteenth century using them."}, {"page": 128, "text": "I borrowed my brother Edmin’s camera and took several shots of the surrounding hills and of majestic Mt."}, {"page": 128, "text": "Pinatubo, which was hidden by clouds earlier, never knowing that these pictures were the last ones to be taken of this sleeping giant. 120 nosneH eisoJ nosneH eisoJ"}, {"page": 129, "text": "AMERICAN ExOdUS June 10, 1991 15,000 Air Force evacuees from Clark squeezed into another military base that was already jampacked with 14,000 Navy personnel Suddenly, it was crunch time for the military officials at Clark."}, {"page": 129, "text": "They began planning the unthinkable: evacuating 15,000 base residents to… where?"}, {"page": 129, "text": "Wallace Air Station in San Fernando, La Union was too small."}, {"page": 129, "text": "So they agreed on Subic and Cubi Point, both in Zambales."}, {"page": 129, "text": "The naval stations were not as large as Clark, but they could serve as temporary shelter until the situation normalized."}, {"page": 129, "text": "The Subic Bay Naval Station had the U.S."}, {"page": 129, "text": "Navy’s best deep-water port in the western Pacific, while the Cubi Point Naval Air Station had a runway that could accommodate large commercial and military planes."}, {"page": 129, "text": "To Clark officials, Subic and Cubi, which are both about 32 km from Mount Pinatubo, were well outside the danger zone and beyond the reach of heavy ash fall—or so they thought. 121 moc.wolleyeerf.pacz"}, {"page": 130, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Clark officials also looked around for a nearer evacuation site for members of the security force, who would stay behind and leave on short notice."}, {"page": 130, "text": "The first suggestion, the far side of the runway, was rejected because officials felt it wasn’t far enough from the danger zone."}, {"page": 130, "text": "The second, the Pampanga Agricultural College (PAC) in Magalang, looked promising."}, {"page": 130, "text": "An advance team was sent to negotiate with the PAC President, who agreed to accommodate the Americans provided Clark engineers made minor repairs on some school facilities. “The only disconcerting aspect of the agricultural college,” wrote Col."}, {"page": 130, "text": "Anderegg, “was that it was directly on the flank of a dormant volcano, Mount Arayat (which) was familiar to anyone who visited or lived at Clark."}, {"page": 130, "text": "Many who heard about the volcano near Clark immediately assumed it was Arayat."}, {"page": 130, "text": "Pinatubo, a small, smoking hill, its top barely visible above the surrounding jungle eight miles west of Clark, was the bad boy.” Pampanga Agricultural College on the flank of Mount Arayat By mid-May, Dr."}, {"page": 130, "text": "Punongbayan still could not tell when the eruption might be, how big it would be, or even “It was not until if it would happen at all. (Dr."}, {"page": 130, "text": "Newhall would early June that return to the United States and totally miss the we could make a eruption.) categorical statement that Pinatubo would The volcanologists admitted to Clark erupt; until then, we officials that volcanology was an inexact science, weren’t sure that it that Pinatubo was unpredictable, and that the would erupt, and we process could unfold very, very slowly, could didn’t want to ‘cry take months or even years, and could stop and wolf’ lest we lose even reverse itself.2 And even if the eruption credibility that might did come, it could be anything between a hiccup be needed in the and the Big One. following months.” To Clark officials who were under pressure Dr."}, {"page": 130, "text": "Punongbayan to design and execute an evacuation plan, this 122"}, {"page": 131, "text": "Magma Rising kind of assessment was simply unacceptable."}, {"page": 131, "text": "How many of the 15,000 would they evacuate?"}, {"page": 131, "text": "How far would they have to be evacuated and how long would they stay there?"}, {"page": 131, "text": "When exactly would the evacuation commence—when the eruption was certain, when it was imminent, or when it was underway?"}, {"page": 131, "text": "And how would they deal with false alarms?"}, {"page": 131, "text": "When the newly appointed Commander of the entire Pacific Air Forces, Gen."}, {"page": 131, "text": "Jimmie Adams, visited Clark in mid-May, he asked to be flown by helicopter over the famous mountain."}, {"page": 131, "text": "He saw the steam clouds and smelled the sulfur but when told that the volcano had not erupted in 500 years, the big boss of the U.S."}, {"page": 131, "text": "Air Force in the Pacific heaved a sigh of relief and said he wasn’t concerned at that point.3 First week of June, volcanologists jumped up when they observed a bulge on the volcano’s slope—a tell-tale sign that the rising magma was now just below the surface."}, {"page": 131, "text": "They raised the alert level from 2 to 3 (“eruption possible within two weeks”)."}, {"page": 131, "text": "USGS and PHIVOLCS relayed the information to Clark and government officials so that they could effect their respective evacuation plans."}, {"page": 131, "text": "The next day, however, when the volcanologists double-checked the bulge, they found out it was nothing but an old rock formation."}, {"page": 131, "text": "Relieved but somewhat embarrassed, they informed the same officials about the mistake, but they all agreed to retain alert level 3."}, {"page": 131, "text": "Some officials began to worry about a sudden eruption for which the present warning system might be inadequate."}, {"page": 131, "text": "Others worried about raising another false alarm which would further erode their credibility."}, {"page": 131, "text": "Not only was Pinatubo unpredictable; it was now turning into a petulant volcano, ‘teasing’ and stressing the already stressed- out scientists.4 (Years later, when scientists studied the record, magma had indeed risen very close to the surface in that first week of June, 1991."}, {"page": 131, "text": "The only thing that prevented Pinatubo from erupting that early was the volcano’s narrow throat—which would eventually be cleared on June 12.) Ironically, the scientists themselves were causing stress on military officials at Clark."}, {"page": 131, "text": "The confused and confusing signals from the supposed experts were coming at a time when officials were under unbelievable pressure to move the largest Air Force base overseas out of harm’s way at a moment’s notice.5 Although Subic was the largest U.S. naval installation in the Pacific, it was already bursting at the 123"}, {"page": 132, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard seams with its own 14,000 residents and limited housing facilities."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Even prior to the influx of 15,000 Clark residents, Subic was already experiencing water rationing, rotating brownouts, and a shortage of beds for 800 of its own personnel, many of whom had to live off-base in nearby Olongapo City."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Plans to build 2,200 more housing units at Subic had had to be deferred pending the outcome of the bases negotiations."}, {"page": 132, "text": "The evacuation plan for Clark would have groups of residents driving out of their respective housing areas with 90-minute intervals, with those living in the Mactan housing area leaving first (because Mactan would be hit first by the pyroclastic flows, according to scientists), followed by residents in housing areas near the Abacan River, where pyroclastic flows were also expected to pass."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Using the bases’ three main roads, the evacuees would converge at the aircraft parking apron, already empty because the 3rd Tactical Fighter Wing planes had been flown out of Clark."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Then they would be herded on the flightline towards either the Main Gate or the Dau exit (the Mabalacat gate and the Sapangbato gate were not in the plan because of their proximity to the Sacobia River and the Abacan River, respectively)."}, {"page": 132, "text": "There was concern over the condition of the highway leading to Subic."}, {"page": 132, "text": "On a normal day, traffic was already slow; adding a few more thousand vehicles on the road would put the traffic to a standstill for hours."}, {"page": 132, "text": "It would also make thousands of Americans sitting ducks for communist rebels and nationalist protesters."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Clark officials also worried that the evacuation might jeopardize the ongoing bases negotiations."}, {"page": 132, "text": "The United States could be accused of blackmail or bully tactics for temporarily abandoning the base to give Filipinos a glimpse into the economic disaster waiting to happen."}, {"page": 132, "text": "For its part, PHIVOLCS was concerned about media speculation that the agency was being pressured by lobby groups to time the volcano’s ‘big bang’ with the expiration of the agreement in September, so that the Americans would lose interest in it."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Punongbayan about this, he retorted, “Ah, wala akong kinalaman dyan."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Masasabi ko ba sa bulkan kung kailan dapat pumutok (I don’t have anything to do with it."}, {"page": 132, "text": "Can I tell a volcano when it should erupt)?”6 Actually, Clark officials were split into two groups: those who wanted to wait until volcanologists were 100% sure the volcano 124"}, {"page": 133, "text": "Magma Rising Julio Sabit PHIVOLCS On June 9 at about 2:30 P.M., short pyroclastic flows (surges?) descended the northwest and west slopes of Pinatubo."}, {"page": 133, "text": "The pyroclastic flows lasted almost 30 minutes."}, {"page": 133, "text": "In my experience with previous eruptions of Mayon, the occurrence of pyroclastic flows signifies that an eruption is on-going."}, {"page": 133, "text": "Punongbayan and rushed a bulletin raising the volcano’s status to Alert Level 5, to indicate that a hazardous eruption was in progress."}, {"page": 133, "text": "The danger zone was expanded to minimize if not avoid destruction of life and property."}, {"page": 133, "text": "A few minutes later, increasing frequency and magnitude of ash explosions were observed but this was not sustained. would erupt, and those who wanted an early evacuation out of fear that a sudden eruption might result in a panicked evacuation that could kill more people than the volcano itself.7 On June 9, the PHIVOLCS monitoring team at Poonbato in Zambales reported seeing billowing ash clouds going down Mount Pinatubo towards the Maraunot River."}, {"page": 133, "text": "The ash clouds reached a height of 5 kilometers and a distance of 5 kilometers from the steaming vents."}, {"page": 133, "text": "The report was enough to prompt the USGS-PHIVOLCS team to raise the alert level to 5 (“eruption in progress”)."}, {"page": 133, "text": "Aetas were again evacuated farther away from the volcano, and Clark officials went on FEN-TV to tell Clark residents to make preparations for an evacuation and to stay tuned for further announcements.8 Later that day, however, aerial reconnaissance on the Zambales side revealed that the volcanologists may have made another error: what the monitoring team had seen earlier was not a pyroclastic flow, but a mere pyroclastic density current which had left only a thin blanket of ash fall in the Maraunot valley."}, {"page": 133, "text": "The next day, the national dailies screamed “Pinatubo erupts!” although local residents saw no change in the appearance of the volcano."}, {"page": 133, "text": "It again gave the skeptics another reason to gloat, but PHIVOLCS did not withdraw the alert level anymore because the pyroclastic density currents, although not technically pyroclastic flows, still represented a significant intensification of volcanic activity.9 125"}, {"page": 134, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard At Clark, military officials did not want to take any more chances."}, {"page": 134, "text": "Already up before dawn, they announced on FEN-TV that the evacuation would commence at 6 A.M."}, {"page": 134, "text": "As the sirens blared, servicemen hauled their sleepy families into cars, while unmarried personnel took the military buses. “No one was happy about leaving,” Col."}, {"page": 134, "text": "Anderegg, said.10 The vehicles, numbering over 6,000, first assembled on the flightline, where volunteers distributed bottled water, snacks and toiletries and took down passengers’ names and relationships."}, {"page": 134, "text": "Then the convoy proceeded to the Main Gate, where many cars stopped to drop off Filipino maids."}, {"page": 134, "text": "Some American families who had gotten attached to their domestic helps brought them along to Subic.11 Bar girls along Fields Avenue took the bus and followed the servicemen to Olongapo.12 But most of the 10,000 Filipino workers at Clark felt abandoned."}, {"page": 134, "text": "According to union president Bobby Flores, with the June 15 payday only five days away, they worried if the payroll had been left behind, if it would be safe from looters, and if someone would be around on June 15 to distribute it.13 By 12 noon, Clark was empty—the first time in its 90-year history."}, {"page": 134, "text": "The six-hour evacuation to Subic appeared to be a success."}, {"page": 134, "text": "They would soon find out, however, that because they had been told they would 126 )retfA sraeY 005 :obutaniP .tM( yayuT niwdE Over 6000 vehicles made their way from Clark to Subic on June 10, raising alarm and derision among Kapampangans who witnessed the exodus"}, {"page": 135, "text": "Magma Rising Levy Laus President/CEO, Laus Group of Companies I saw the convoy of Americans near the Dolores junction."}, {"page": 135, "text": "The U.S. military guarded every corner and intersection all the way to Subic."}, {"page": 135, "text": "They, and not our policemen, were in charge of the situation."}, {"page": 135, "text": "There were even helicopters following the convoy."}, {"page": 135, "text": "And being the inquisitive and adventurous person that I was, when I heard that Pinatubo was ready to erupt, I put up camp in Botolan where PHIVOLCS and some newsmen were staying."}, {"page": 135, "text": "My friend Greg Castro assured me that it was safe to spend the night there."}, {"page": 135, "text": "Fortunately or unfortunately, the volcano did not erupt that night so the next morning, June 11, I packed up and returned to Pampanga."}, {"page": 135, "text": "The next day, Independence Day, while I was working in my office at Carworld, Pinatubo erupted."}, {"page": 135, "text": "At that time, we had no clear appreciation of geography."}, {"page": 135, "text": "We thought Pinatubo being in Zambales was quite distant from Pampanga. be gone for only three days, they had brought clothing and food for only three days and had left behind critical items like marriage licenses, insurance policies, prescription medicines, “The Americans are and pets."}, {"page": 135, "text": "This miscalculation would have a causing panic."}, {"page": 135, "text": "I feel great impact on their prolonged stay at Subic, bad towards these Americans."}, {"page": 135, "text": "They are especially during the eruption when the naval overactive (sic)."}, {"page": 135, "text": "We station’s supplies and services bogged down, feel safe here."}, {"page": 135, "text": "No as well as during the second evacuation (to one is affected.” Cebu and later to Guam) when the immigration Mayor Antonio Abad Santos officials required the evacuees to present of Angeles City documents to filter out illegal entrants."}, {"page": 135, "text": "At Subic, the evacuees, who had started “The mayor is entitled arriving as early as 8 a.m., were crowding the to his own opinion.” Sampaguita Club for registration."}, {"page": 135, "text": "The rest waited US Navy Lieutenant Commander Kevin Mukri on the football field, where they sweltered for Subic spokesman hours."}, {"page": 135, "text": "Some even dug holes in the ground under their cars and crawled into them. “He is talking out of Because most living quarters at Subic (as well ignorance.” as nearby Cubi Point Naval Air Station) were Dr."}, {"page": 136, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard The evacuating vehicles first assembled on the Clark runway where they registered and got free bottled water and chocolate bars."}, {"page": 136, "text": "The evacuation of 15,000 personnel to Subic took six hours. already occupied by Navy personnel, the evacuees were led to the remaining unoccupied homes in the San Miguel housing area and the Navy recreation area on Grande Island."}, {"page": 136, "text": "A few Navy families opened their doors to Air Force families."}, {"page": 136, "text": "But the great majority of evacuees were in gymnasiums, classrooms, chapels and any place they could find a roof over their heads."}, {"page": 136, "text": "Those who were married to local girls were allowed to join their wives’ families outside Subic provided they stayed within 30 kilometers of Subic."}, {"page": 136, "text": "That night, thousands of Americans slept on cardboard beds on hallways and basketball courts."}, {"page": 136, "text": "It was a fitful sleep to say the least—the base commissary had run out of disposable diapers and dog food within hours of the evacuees’ arrival.14 “There is a lot of stress involved,” Lieut."}, {"page": 136, "text": "Kevin Mukri, Subic spokesman, told reporters covering the exodus. “We have families doubling up and bachelors quadrupling up."}, {"page": 136, "text": "It’s like a small town of 14,000 having to double itself overnight.”15 Back at Clark, a contingent of 1,200 personnel stayed behind: civil engineers, heavy equipment operators, firemen, cooks and communications specialists, including a 960-strong security force to patrol the base against looters.16 The USGS-PHIVOLCS team, of course, stayed."}, {"page": 136, "text": "In addition, some 1,300 Philippine Air Force troopers 128"}, {"page": 137, "text": "Magma Rising were left to do their own securing of the base."}, {"page": 137, "text": "A revised Military Bases Agreement in 1979, which established Philippine sovereignty over Clark, had created the Clark Air Base Command (CABCOM) as co-administrator of the military installation. “We will not abandon Clark until after lava from Mount Pinatubo reaches our doorsteps,” vowed Maj."}, {"page": 137, "text": "Loven Abadia, who, as the Commanding General of the Philippine Air Force, was also concurrently the CABCOM head. (He should not be confused with his brother, Gen."}, {"page": 137, "text": "Lisandro Abadia, who was at the time the Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces of the Philippines.) But if it was any indication of things to come, the Crow Valley Bombing and Gunnery Range at nearby Capas had already been raided by looters, who carted away every moveable equipment including rolls of copper wire, tools and furniture. “If they had a truck, they could have taken away the power generator,” sighed Brig."}, {"page": 137, "text": "Leopoldo Acot, CABCOM vice commander.17 In anticipation of heavy ash fall, all Clark “The Americans left aircraft were flown to Cubi Point, including in haste and in the MC-130 transport planes, MH-53 Pave Low process, created panic in Angeles helicopters, and C-12 King Air transport planes.18 City."}, {"page": 137, "text": "Acting in typical When newspapers reported that six nuclear colonial fashion, warheads were in one or some of these planes, these Americans have U.S."}, {"page": 137, "text": "Embassy spokesman Stanley Schrager said, regarded Filipinos as “I know nothing at all about these warheads. subjects whom they That’s all I can say.” can dispose of as they Meanwhile, Filipino residents outside Clark please."}, {"page": 137, "text": "For them, were mystified by the Americans’ sudden even their dogs and departure."}, {"page": 137, "text": "Did Clark know something they cats had to come didn’t?"}, {"page": 137, "text": "Antonio Abad Santos, the outspoken first.” mayor of Angeles City, told reporters, “The Marilen Danguilan, Emmeline Verzosa and Jamie Americans are causing panic."}, {"page": 137, "text": "I feel bad towards Tapales-Oakes, London School of these Americans."}, {"page": 138, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard feel safe here."}, {"page": 138, "text": "Nobody is affected.” His remarks immediately drew sharp reactions, from Lieut."}, {"page": 138, "text": "Mukri who said, “The mayor is entitled to his own opinion, but our duty is to ensure the safety of our own personnel,” and from Dr."}, {"page": 138, "text": "Punongbayan who said, “He is talking out of ignorance.”19 Meanwhile, at the Pinatubo Volcano Observatory, the USGS- PHIVOLCS team continued to pore over the data coming from their monitoring devices, as well as from satellite images being sent from the United States."}, {"page": 138, "text": "At least they could now limit the possible eruption scenarios to only three: (1) a Plinian eruption with pyroclastic flows going northwest (Zambales side), which was “highly probable;” (2) a larger eruption with pyroclastic flows going east (Pampanga side) and crossing a topographic divide towards populated areas, which was “moderately probable;” and (3) small explosions going on for weeks, months, even years before an actual eruption, also “moderately probable.”20 With 15,000 American evacuees sweating it out in Subic, scientists were under pressure to produce evidence that the evacuation was not a mistake. 1Anderegg, pp. 14-15. 2Ibid., p. 17. 3Ibid., p. 21. 4Fire and Mud, p. 80. 5Anderegg, p. 25. 6 Philippine Daily Inquirer (June 12, 1991). 7Anderegg, p. 26. 8Ibid., p. 27. 9 Fire and Mud, pp. 451-452. 10 Anderegg, p. 28. 11 Ibid. 12 Philippine Daily Inquirer, ibid. 13 Ibid. (June 17, 1991). 14 Anderegg, p. 28. 15 Philippine Daily Inquirer (June 12, 1991). 16 Anderegg, ibid. 17 Philippine Daily Inquirer, ibid. 18 Ibid. (June 13, 1991). 19 Ibid. (June 12, 1991). 20 Fire and Mud, pp. 80-81. 21 Philippine Daily Inquirer (June 17, 1991). 130"}, {"page": 140, "text": "June 12 June 13 storm Diding develops off samar June 12, 1991 - June 14, 1991 Apt Metaphors Kapampangans described the June 12 eruption cloud as “cauliflower” and “mushroom.” Their choice of small, familiar and comforting objects as metaphors for a huge, unsettling event helped them cope."}, {"page": 141, "text": "June 14 typhoon Diding with typhoon Diding 195-kph winds off Bicol about to enter luzon Aviationspectator.com"}, {"page": 143, "text": "dAY OF INdEPENdENCE June 12, 1991 Volcanoes are pots of magma simmering over a massive underground furnace."}, {"page": 143, "text": "A regular eruption is when the stew in the pot boils over, while a cataclysmic eruption is when the stove collapses and burns the whole kitchen down All the speculations and uncertainties about when and how big the eruption would be, ended abruptly on the morning of June 12—Independence Day, of all days—when Mount Pinatubo produced a billowing gigantic column of ash and steam that shot up to the blue sky at an astonishing speed of 1,300 feet per second."}, {"page": 143, "text": "The weathermen at Cubi Point (the air station of Subic) measured the column’s height as exceeding their radar’s height range (18 kilometers)."}, {"page": 143, "text": "When it reached the altitude of at least 19 kilometers, it spread out to form a mushroom cloud, similar to a nuclear explosion. 135 lumuY eliceC"}, {"page": 144, "text": "PINATUBO: The Volcano In Our Backyard Elmer Buasan Station Manager, GV-FM Because we were both single and from Bulacan, GV-FM owner Manny Galang and I made the station our living quarters."}, {"page": 144, "text": "GV-FM at the time was broadcasting from the 6th floor of Howville Bldg. in downtown Angeles."}, {"page": 144, "text": "From there we could see the smoke on Mount Pinatubo."}, {"page": 144, "text": "We were even joking that it was just the Aetas making a bonfire."}, {"page": 144, "text": "The sight was scary enough to cause pandemonium."}, {"page": 144, "text": "Church bells pealed, passenger jeepneys sped away without stopping for passengers, and women ran in the streets weeping and calling their children’s names."}, {"page": 144, "text": "An Independence Day parade in downtown Angeles broke up, the drum and bugle corps scampering in all directions."}, {"page": 144, "text": "At Clark, those who had been left behind also panicked. “They didn’t know (where) they were supposed to be going,” Col."}, {"page": 144, "text": "Anderegg said. “All manner of vehicles, every kind of vehicle you’ve ever seen and people in every state of disarray and undress you’ve ever seen.” One pickup truck had its driver steering with his left hand as his right hand held a camera out the window to videotape the eruption cloud.1 About 600 members of the Clark contingent group evacuated to PAC in Magalang."}, {"page": 144, "text": "The security force maintained patrol duty, focusing on the Mactan housing area where they chased away looters, including one who was hauling 10 bicycles in a pull cart.2 Two buses from Subic had just unloaded Clark servicemen who returned to collect their remaining household items when the eruption occurred, sending the servicemen back to the buses, and the buses back to Subic.3 Actually, Clark officials were relieved that Pinatubo had finally erupted and that its eruption had not caused any damage nor seemed to have posed a real threat to the military base."}, {"page": 144, "text": "The eruption was a vindication of their decision to evacuate."}, {"page": 144, "text": "Had the 15,000 personnel not left Clark, the sight of the mushroom cloud would have thrown the military base into utter chaos."}, {"page": 144, "text": "Meanwhile, the USGS-PHIVOLCS team, which had moved to an alternate command post near the Dau exit (additional 8 kilometers away from the volcano), cautioned Clark officials that the eruption 136"}];